WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.400
[Amit Varma]: Before you listen to this episode of the scene in the unseen, I have a recommendation for

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:13.600
[Amit Varma]: you. Do check out Pulya Bazi hosted by Saurabh Chandra and Pranay Kotesane, two really good

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:17.880
[Amit Varma]: friends of mine. Kickass podcast in Hindi. It's amazing.

00:00:17.880 --> 00:00:23.840
[Amit Varma]: Liberals, progressives, conservatives, libertarians. I have a problem with these labels. In fact,

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:29.160
[Amit Varma]: I have four problems with these labels. Problem one, they have changed meaning over time.

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:34.200
[Amit Varma]: The word liberal meant one thing in the 19th century and means quite another in the 21st.

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:37.600
[Amit Varma]: And it means different things in different parts of the world. For example, American

00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:42.320
[Amit Varma]: liberals often have the opposite beliefs to European liberals and classical liberals and

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:47.720
[Amit Varma]: left liberals are often at loggerheads with one another. Problem two, the proper nouns

00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:52.880
[Amit Varma]: often do not mean what the common noun does. For example, I meet too many liberals who

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:58.440
[Amit Varma]: are anything but liberal. So many progressives are certainly not progressive and many conservatives

00:00:58.440 --> 00:01:04.280
[Amit Varma]: are actually quite radical. Problem three, these labels have acquired a tribal significance.

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:08.440
[Amit Varma]: And if you call yourself say libertarian, it is held as meaning that you belong to a

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:13.320
[Amit Varma]: tribe of people who call themselves libertarian and not that you believe in a certain set

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:18.080
[Amit Varma]: of values. And you then become part of the tribal warfare between liberals and conservatives

00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:23.200
[Amit Varma]: and progressives and libertarians. And the discussion becomes heated and personal, degenerating

00:01:23.200 --> 00:01:29.200
[Amit Varma]: to abuse rather than calm and rational revolving around values. Problem four, these labels

00:01:29.200 --> 00:01:34.640
[Amit Varma]: are meaningless in an Indian context. Politics in India is not divided in the left right

00:01:34.640 --> 00:01:39.640
[Amit Varma]: spectrum as it is in the West and identity politics dominates here. Though I did explore

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:44.480
[Amit Varma]: in episode 131 of the scene in the unseen, the theory that ideological fault lines do

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:51.160
[Amit Varma]: exist in Indian politics, but around different issues than in the West. And yet, here I am

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:56.360
[Amit Varma]: doing an episode called the Indian conservative. Why is this? Well, here's the thing. The scene

00:01:56.360 --> 00:02:02.600
[Amit Varma]: in the unseen is basically driven by my intellectual curiosity about ideas and events. And over

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:07.440
[Amit Varma]: the last few months, I have been reexamining a prior belief I held about India, that there

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:12.440
[Amit Varma]: was no such thing as conservatism in India. I held the view that conservatism as it is

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:17.840
[Amit Varma]: in the West, say Burkean conservatism was missing in India, and that the term conservative

00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:23.720
[Amit Varma]: was used as a respectable fig leaf by communal bigots who were simply indulging in identity

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:29.040
[Amit Varma]: politics. This is partly true, but I've come to realize that it's a simplistic view, and

00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:33.400
[Amit Varma]: that there have been strains of conservative thought in India. And if we want to understand

00:02:33.400 --> 00:02:40.000
[Amit Varma]: this country as it is today, we need to engage with it seriously and respectfully. My intellectual

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.200
[Amit Varma]: journey on the subject has partly taken place in public through various episodes of the

00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:49.040
[Amit Varma]: scene in the unseen, in which I've spoken to guests like Aakar Patel, Suyash Rai, Rahul

00:02:49.040 --> 00:02:54.560
[Amit Varma]: Verma and Akshay Mukul. Today, I take one more step in that journey with a fine author

00:02:54.560 --> 00:02:58.960
[Amit Varma]: who has written an erudite book called the Indian conservative, which is therefore the

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:04.640
[Amit Varma]: subject of this episode, and of my continuing exploration of the hidden currents that drive

00:03:04.640 --> 00:03:09.240
[Amit Varma]: our great nation.

