[Amit Varma]: running. Keep it smooth. Jerry, welcome to the scene and the unseen. Thank you so much

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:33.720
[Amit Varma]: Amit. Before we get down to talking about your book, The Indian Conservative, which

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:38.280
[Amit Varma]: I greatly enjoyed reading very thought provoking. Let's first talk a little bit about your personal

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:46.400
[Guest]: journey like what makes Jerry Rao, Jerry Rao? Well, I guess some relatively standard kind

00:05:46.400 --> 00:05:56.080
[Guest]: of Indian middle class background on the 50s, 60s, 70s. My father was an official in the

00:05:56.080 --> 00:06:01.840
[Guest]: government and he got transferred from place to place and we as a family moved with him

00:06:01.840 --> 00:06:09.280
[Guest]: from place to place. We are South Indian originally from the state of Tamil Nadu, but we are not

00:06:09.280 --> 00:06:17.280
[Guest]: Tamilians. We are Kannada speaking people. My family roots go back to Coimbatore. But

00:06:17.280 --> 00:06:23.600
[Guest]: for more than 100 years now, 120 years, we've been in Madras. So Madras is where I finished

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:33.040
[Guest]: school and did my college. So that kind of gives you a smattering of Hindi, a smattering

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:40.680
[Guest]: of Tamil, a smattering of Kannada and pretty much otherwise English is the way and a little

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:48.520
[Guest]: bit of Sanskrit too in fairness. But that's pretty much the way one's linguistic narrative,

00:06:48.520 --> 00:06:55.920
[Guest]: if you will, pans out. Conservative family, very traditional, religious, every single

00:06:55.920 --> 00:07:03.240
[Guest]: religious festival occasion was observed, visited lots of temples as a child and as

00:07:03.240 --> 00:07:11.840
[Guest]: a teenager. So from that perspective, very much rooted in things Indian, also in things

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:19.680
[Guest]: of the Raj, because my grandfathers, both of them were very much into English literature

00:07:19.680 --> 00:07:26.720
[Guest]: and so and into an appreciation of the finer things of the British Raj. So that too came

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:33.640
[Guest]: through in the stuff. Oddly enough, oddly enough, since you ask, one of the incidents

00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:42.400
[Guest]: that I've been remembering recently in different contexts is when our family went to Bhakra

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:53.480
[Guest]: in 1960, I think, and the dam was still being built. And my father, I remember telling us,

00:07:53.480 --> 00:08:00.960
[Guest]: look, what a grand thing Panditji is building for us. So there was that whole sense of the

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:08.880
[Guest]: 1960s effervescent patriotism, the looking forward to a great future and all that and

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:17.000
[Guest]: pride and all that. So that too was very much part of my upbringing. After that, after college,

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:22.760
[Guest]: I went to business school, went to Ahmedabad, then got into banking and went around the

00:08:22.760 --> 00:08:30.160
[Guest]: world and took a couple of years off, went back to university, University of Chicago,

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:38.160
[Guest]: then came back into banking, spent a lot of years in banking about 25 years, left in California

00:08:38.160 --> 00:08:45.880
[Guest]: in 1998, and went into it. That was a 10 year stint in it. Then we sold off our company

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:51.960
[Guest]: and then I moved on. And since then, I've been an investor in a variety of companies,

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:59.120
[Guest]: including housing finance company, which I exited some time back, and a housing development

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:02.760
[Guest]: company where I'm still involved as a promoter.

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:06.400
[Amit Varma]: And what's your intellectual journey through this period? Like, like you'd mentioned when

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:09.760
[Amit Varma]: we had coffee before this, that you were a socialist in college.

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:11.320
[Amit Varma]: Yes, that is true.

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:15.120
[Amit Varma]: What was that journey like? How did you change? Was it that you were, you know, you did your

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:19.640
[Amit Varma]: MBA and you're out in the real world and you're mugged by reality, or?

00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:29.760
[Guest]: I think definitely the socialist thing was very strong in my college days, I would say

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:40.120
[Guest]: age 16 through 20 time period. It was also remember the time when Vietnam War protests

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:49.240
[Guest]: were taking place all over the world, including in sleepy Madras. And the Berkeley and Paris

00:09:49.240 --> 00:09:54.240
[Guest]: and all these things were, were very much part of the, the consciousness of people like

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:59.760
[Guest]: us. And in India, we had a charismatic leader who was nationalizing banks and troubling

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:08.120
[Guest]: Rajas. So, there was a, there was that wave of, of popular socialist feeling, which was

00:10:08.120 --> 00:10:16.040
[Guest]: very much part of my consciousness and my, my interest. And I've written a poem somewhere

00:10:16.040 --> 00:10:22.680
[Guest]: where I mentioned the fact that when we were young, we read Lenin's State and Revolution.

00:10:22.680 --> 00:10:28.720
[Guest]: Kind of tells you something about the nature of the time. Over, I think it is not just

00:10:28.720 --> 00:10:37.120
[Guest]: MBA and so on. It is over the years, gradually, with greater exposure to different kinds of

00:10:37.120 --> 00:10:45.160
[Guest]: texts, different kinds of people, that conservatism, first, it was actually on the economic side,

00:10:45.160 --> 00:10:55.480
[Guest]: a movement towards markets as being more consequentially efficient. But then I would say in the last

00:10:55.480 --> 00:11:03.800
[Guest]: 30 odd years, it's been, or 25 years, it's been more from the moral side as to what,

00:11:03.800 --> 00:11:11.320
[Guest]: what is appropriate for human beings, that the, the intellectual journey has, has taken

00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:20.840
[Guest]: place the way it has. To some extent, I think, constantly reinforced by the fact that at

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:31.020
[Guest]: least for the last 20 odd years, yeah, no, maybe 25 years, I've been doing a lot of pilgrimages

00:11:31.020 --> 00:11:38.840
[Guest]: and temple visits. And that somehow tends to reinforce a certain idea of India, and

00:11:38.840 --> 00:11:45.440
[Guest]: a certain idea of what it is that one needs to conserve about India, about our own society,

00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:49.280
[Guest]: and therefore what one needs to conserve about human beings in general.

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:54.320
[Amit Varma]: And who are the sort of thinkers who influenced you? Like, are there any, like, one question

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:57.720
[Amit Varma]: I often ask my guests is that, is there any book which changed the way you look at the

00:11:57.720 --> 00:12:01.320
[Amit Varma]: world? Which is perhaps a little simplistic, they often won't be just one book, there'll

00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:04.280
[Amit Varma]: be multiple books. But if I were to post it to you?

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:14.200
[Guest]: I think the most important influence, both from an aesthetic and a, and a kind of moral

00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:24.120
[Guest]: perspective is T.S. Eliot. Because I think the development of Eliot between Wasteland

00:12:24.120 --> 00:12:30.200
[Guest]: and Journey of the Magi, which is my favorite poem, I read it at least once or twice a month,

00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:40.920
[Guest]: sometimes aloud. And for Quartets, kind of established for me that there is continuity

00:12:40.920 --> 00:12:49.120
[Guest]: in what we as human beings do. And to snap that thread of continuity and to kind of do

00:12:49.120 --> 00:12:55.240
[Guest]: something radical or revolutionary and break down and try to build anew is something that

00:12:55.240 --> 00:13:03.720
[Guest]: I've started detesting quite a bit. So I would say Eliot. Initially, Eliot was a shock, as

00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:10.720
[Guest]: what Hugh Hefner says, is a neurasthenic shock of reading Profrock. But over time, Eliot

00:13:10.720 --> 00:13:21.040
[Guest]: was not. I remember once going to London and I visited St. Mary Woolnott Church. I went

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:26.760
[Guest]: down King William Street to where St. Mary Woolnott kept the hour. It's in Wasteland.

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:32.360
[Guest]: And then I went to the other church where there's Ionian white and gold. And then one

00:13:32.360 --> 00:13:43.880
[Guest]: started getting a feel that, that in seeking to maintain continuity with tradition, Eliot

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:50.840
[Guest]: was trying to give us an extremely important lesson about, and he does it, of course, in

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:55.640
[Guest]: the aesthetic literary world. But I think it's equally applicable in the political,

00:13:55.640 --> 00:14:05.040
[Guest]: social, aesthetic worlds. And the second influence, I would say, is Smith. Adam Smith, the early

00:14:05.040 --> 00:14:06.040
[Guest]: Smith.

00:14:06.040 --> 00:14:07.040
[Guest]: Moral sentiments.

00:14:07.040 --> 00:14:12.640
[Guest]: Theory of moral sentiments. And this, I never knew about it, frankly. I, like everyone else,

00:14:12.640 --> 00:14:18.680
[Guest]: one read or one skimmed through Wealth of Nations and quoted one sentence from it. That's

00:14:18.680 --> 00:14:28.080
[Guest]: the way Standard Economics 101 works. But several years ago, 10, 15 years ago, I was

00:14:28.080 --> 00:14:37.640
[Guest]: at a longish meeting with Professor Amartya Sen when he kind of directed me to go and

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:48.240
[Guest]: read Theory of Moral Sentiments, which subsequently, of course, I did. And it opened up. The fact

00:14:48.240 --> 00:14:52.680
[Guest]: that it was published a decade earlier than The Wealth of Nations and precedes it, and

00:14:52.680 --> 00:15:03.080
[Guest]: in fact is the foundation for the later capitalism that Smith developed, struck me. Again, this

00:15:03.080 --> 00:15:09.440
[Guest]: whole thing that ideas evolve. That is, Bacon says something, somebody else says something,

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:14.800
[Guest]: you build on what Bacon says. You know, it's not, it's not something that comes in a sui

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:22.200
[Guest]: generis at one particular point in time. So that's the thing that I kind of saw in Smith's

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:29.200
[Guest]: evolution and that there is a moral purpose to markets, which is much more than the consequentialist

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:36.280
[Guest]: efficiency, which the Butcher Baker quotation talks about. I would say in recent times in

00:15:36.280 --> 00:15:43.560
[Guest]: the last 10 years, Scruton, Roger Scruton, Roger Scruton has been important because he's

00:15:43.560 --> 00:15:47.960
[Guest]: defending a society which is, actually, I wrote this about Naipaul too. I don't know,

00:15:47.960 --> 00:15:52.200
[Guest]: you can go back and look at one of the essays I wrote in the Indian Express several years

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:59.960
[Guest]: ago when I was talking about Naipaul, comparing him where he is talking about the decline

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:07.880
[Guest]: of modern civilization, particularly Western civilization, comparing him to a kind of Latin

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:16.840
[Guest]: epigramist living in Tuscany in the year 409 AD, one year before Rome was sacked by Alaric.

00:16:16.840 --> 00:16:26.560
[Guest]: So there's this sense of foreboding that Naipaul, as a great conservative, has that in not preserving

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:33.040
[Guest]: and in not building on what we have inherited from humans and trying to jettison that, we

00:16:33.040 --> 00:16:38.520
[Guest]: make great mistakes. And Scruton is very much at the center of that, at least as far as

00:16:38.520 --> 00:16:44.080
[Guest]: England is concerned. Because the Church of England is in decline, church music is in

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:53.760
[Guest]: decline. Shakespeare is no longer fashionable. People don't care about common law. All the

00:16:53.760 --> 00:17:03.800
[Guest]: things that matter to keeping the English traditions going are what Scruton talks about.

00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:08.080
[Guest]: But it's not completely dead. The important thing is they're in decline, they're under

00:17:08.080 --> 00:17:13.400
[Guest]: assault, but I think they'll come back. And there is a sense of optimism also, if you

00:17:13.400 --> 00:17:19.440
[Guest]: see in my book, at the end of it, that it's not completely over. John Major made a very

00:17:19.440 --> 00:17:25.280
[Guest]: interesting statement, I think when, which the cricket commentator John Arlott died,

00:17:25.280 --> 00:17:32.160
[Guest]: Major said, English summers will never be the same again. You know, it's a way of kind

00:17:32.160 --> 00:17:40.360
[Guest]: of keeping in touch with and to some extent, conservatism is an outlook, it's an approach.

00:17:40.360 --> 00:17:42.320
[Guest]: It's less an ideology.

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:45.600
[Amit Varma]: What I'm then going to do since you brought Scruton up is I'm actually going to quote

00:17:45.600 --> 00:17:51.000
[Amit Varma]: from one of his recent books on conservatism. And I have a question for you based on that.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:55.280
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I initially thought that we'll talk about the roots of conservatism starting from

00:17:55.280 --> 00:18:02.000
[Amit Varma]: Burke onwards, and we'll get to that. But since you brought up Scruton, he makes a point

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.440
[Amit Varma]: in his book, which is a point that you have also made at length in yours, which is I'll

00:18:05.440 --> 00:18:11.040
[Amit Varma]: quote him, conservatism is not by nature an international cause. It takes its character

00:18:11.040 --> 00:18:17.200
[Amit Varma]: from local questions, and the loves and suspicions that thrive in specific places and times,

00:18:17.200 --> 00:18:23.720
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. And then he goes on to say, conservatives believe, quote, the root of politics is settlement.

00:18:23.720 --> 00:18:28.120
[Amit Varma]: This is he's put in italics, settlement, the motive in human beings that binds them to

00:18:28.120 --> 00:18:32.740
[Amit Varma]: the place, the customs, the history and the people that are theirs, stop quote. And these

00:18:32.740 --> 00:18:38.000
[Amit Varma]: concerns come out in what you just said about how, you know, English culture is declining

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:43.080
[Amit Varma]: in these various ways you pointed out. And that, but that is a lament, which it also

00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:47.680
[Amit Varma]: seems to me it might be said, it's a two part, it's one observation and a question. And the

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:51.400
[Amit Varma]: observation is, it might be said that that is a lament of Scruton and people like him

00:18:51.400 --> 00:18:56.360
[Amit Varma]: is not necessarily a lament of England, because England itself has changed partly through

00:18:56.360 --> 00:19:02.200
[Amit Varma]: immigration, much as America has been completely transformed through immigration. And the danger

00:19:02.200 --> 00:19:08.120
[Amit Varma]: that a conservative might make there is hold on to a notion of it, which is an archaic

00:19:08.120 --> 00:19:12.440
[Amit Varma]: notion. And just because they value a particular aspect of it doesn't mean that others who

00:19:12.440 --> 00:19:20.080
[Amit Varma]: come from different traditions necessarily do. And my question really is about the local

00:19:20.080 --> 00:19:26.120
[Amit Varma]: nature of conservatism, as you stress, and through most of history, individuals have

00:19:26.120 --> 00:19:30.200
[Amit Varma]: had one geography, that's the place around them, the town where they live, or whatever,

00:19:30.200 --> 00:19:35.400
[Amit Varma]: it's a physical geography. But today, it could be said that we all inhabit many different

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:42.720
[Amit Varma]: geographies that are not bound by physical space. Like, my neighbours are not just those

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:47.160
[Amit Varma]: who live in the flat next door in Bombay, but they are also people who are on the same

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:52.760
[Amit Varma]: WhatsApp group with me from across the world, or whatever. And therefore, my traditions

00:19:52.760 --> 00:19:57.000
[Amit Varma]: are not just the traditions are imbibed from the physical spaces around me or the physical

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:02.920
[Amit Varma]: culture in those physical spaces, but also from the whole globe, I mean, with what technology

00:20:02.920 --> 00:20:05.600
[Guest]: has done. So as a conservative, how do you respond to that?

00:20:05.600 --> 00:20:10.880
[Guest]: Yeah, let's, let's, of all the things you've said, the one word that I would kind of really

00:20:10.880 --> 00:20:18.400
[Guest]: object to is the word archaic, which is said in a kind of derogatory manner.

00:20:18.400 --> 00:20:21.680
[Amit Varma]: I'm not saying it's archaic. I'm saying it might be archaic. That's what I meant, just

00:20:21.680 --> 00:20:22.680
[Guest]: to clarify.

00:20:22.680 --> 00:20:30.760
[Guest]: But my point is, so be it. The Magna Carta is archaic, Shakespeare is archaic, Handel

00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:39.400
[Guest]: is archaic. So do we therefore, very soon, the Beatles may be seen as archaic. So do

00:20:39.400 --> 00:20:46.920
[Guest]: we therefore jettison? And this is what Eliot, that's why I started with Eliot. Eliot goes

00:20:46.920 --> 00:20:53.040
[Guest]: back to Donne. He goes back to earlier metaphysical poets, goes back to Dante. In fact, he goes

00:20:53.040 --> 00:21:00.680
[Guest]: back all the way to Radharani Kopanishad, to go back to the kind of human continuity,

00:21:00.680 --> 00:21:07.560
[Guest]: the chain of continuity, where there's a gradual development evolution. So I think, yes, England

00:21:07.560 --> 00:21:13.360
[Guest]: is changing. England is not today what it was 500 years ago. A hundred years ago, it

00:21:13.360 --> 00:21:19.440
[Guest]: is not what it was 400 years ago. Nobody is saying that there is no change. The only concern

00:21:19.440 --> 00:21:27.800
[Guest]: is in the course of change, are we abandoning good things? If we abandon bad things, that's

00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:33.800
[Guest]: perfectly fine with conservatives, as Desirelius, Burke, Scruton have all said in different

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:44.920
[Guest]: contexts. But if we give up, who will be the loser if we give up? If tomorrow we are no

00:21:44.920 --> 00:21:52.400
[Guest]: longer able to sing Tyagaraja Kritis in the ragas that he composed them in, who is the

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:58.160
[Guest]: loser? You can say, hey, that's archaic. But our view is, hey, it's worth defending. By

00:21:58.160 --> 00:22:04.720
[Guest]: calling it archaic, you can't dismiss it. In fact, we think the old has special value.

00:22:04.720 --> 00:22:09.240
[Guest]: What was the second question you were asking around that?

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:14.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll come back to it. Let me kind of sort of respond to this to clarify sort of what

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:19.920
[Amit Varma]: I meant. And I'm not, again, talking about reform and political changes and so on, just

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:24.560
[Amit Varma]: in the realm of culture, for example. Let's say that the Englishman I'm thinking of is

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:29.840
[Amit Varma]: a second generation Bangladeshi immigrant. His parents immigrated to London or Suffolk

00:22:29.840 --> 00:22:33.640
[Amit Varma]: or wherever, they set up a restaurant, he runs a restaurant. So that's a stereotype.

00:22:33.640 --> 00:22:38.000
[Amit Varma]: He does whatever there. But he considers himself English. He's born and brought up in England.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:42.040
[Amit Varma]: He speaks a language. He is an Englishman. He'll even cheer for the England cricket team.

00:22:42.040 --> 00:22:46.280
[Amit Varma]: But he doesn't listen to Handel. Maybe he listens to Pawan Das Ball, right? Or he listens

00:22:46.280 --> 00:22:50.200
[Amit Varma]: to whatever he wants to, which is a question of individual choice. And maybe in a certain

00:22:50.200 --> 00:22:55.360
[Amit Varma]: sense, he's a cultural conservative that he's preserving those elements of his culture.

00:22:55.360 --> 00:23:00.200
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, from that point of view, it could be argued that, say, Scruton's lament

00:23:00.200 --> 00:23:06.920
[Amit Varma]: that Handel is not being listened to is perfectly legitimate as a personal lament. But can it

00:23:06.920 --> 00:23:09.560
[Amit Varma]: be a lament on behalf of society itself?

00:23:09.560 --> 00:23:17.640
[Guest]: I think the Bangladeshi immigrant, who is now an English person, would actually be better

00:23:17.640 --> 00:23:27.160
[Guest]: off, is my personal view, not forgetting the Baul music at all, but by greater acquaintanceship

00:23:27.160 --> 00:23:33.800
[Guest]: with Handel, because he is living in a country to which Handel is given so much. And I think

00:23:33.800 --> 00:23:39.440
[Guest]: that is important. For instance, you and I live in what's now called Mumbai, used to

00:23:39.440 --> 00:23:52.200
[Guest]: be called Bombay. I think it only helps us to be sensitive, enthusiastic, involved in

00:23:52.200 --> 00:23:59.400
[Guest]: Ganpati festivals or in the Varkari annual pilgrimage, because we are here. It doesn't

00:23:59.400 --> 00:24:06.680
[Guest]: mean you forget whatever Hindi literature you're acquainted with, or I forget Tamil

00:24:06.680 --> 00:24:15.880
[Guest]: or Kannada, but it behooves us, to Scruton's point, to be part of the landscape where we

00:24:15.880 --> 00:24:20.560
[Guest]: are. And I think this is an important... Yes, and the landscape changes. I'm not saying

00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:27.560
[Guest]: it doesn't change. Bombay was Kalachuri, then it was Adil Shahi, then it was Mughal maybe

00:24:27.560 --> 00:24:32.560
[Guest]: for some time, then it was Portuguese, and it was British, and now it's Free India. So

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:40.040
[Guest]: it's changed. But that doesn't mean that certain things, for instance, if you do live here,

00:24:40.040 --> 00:24:45.800
[Guest]: to be enchanted by Elephanta, by the Maheshamurthy there, I think is part of... You can't simply

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:50.800
[Guest]: say, oh, I've come from a foreign place, I'm only going to be interested in things thousand

00:24:50.800 --> 00:24:56.960
[Guest]: miles away. I think you lose out. And that's the point that Scruton is making, that in

00:24:56.960 --> 00:25:02.760
[Guest]: not associating with a... And your point you made, I'll come back to that, the virtual

00:25:02.760 --> 00:25:08.960
[Guest]: and the physical. Yes, conservatives are very much into physical. We love architecture.

00:25:08.960 --> 00:25:14.640
[Guest]: We're very much into landscapes, forests. I wrote many years ago that if you don't love

00:25:14.640 --> 00:25:24.600
[Guest]: water bodies, lakes, rivers, waterfalls, forests, mountains, hills, then you don't love India,

00:25:24.600 --> 00:25:31.760
[Guest]: because that's what the country is all about. So the physical thing is extremely important.

00:25:31.760 --> 00:25:39.640
[Guest]: And I think conservatives would feel profoundly, profoundly anxious if somebody is going to

00:25:39.640 --> 00:25:48.760
[Guest]: spend the whole day sitting on a laptop, talking to people thousands of miles away digitally,

00:25:48.760 --> 00:25:54.280
[Guest]: and not be concerned much about the physical landscape around him or her. That would upset

00:25:54.280 --> 00:26:00.360
[Guest]: us. So yes, the digital world is real, you can't run away from it. But we would hope

00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:05.640
[Guest]: that there'd be a balance and a return to appreciating the immediate physical.

00:26:05.640 --> 00:26:11.760
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. Let's kind of get back on track and talk a little bit about Burke. What does

00:26:11.760 --> 00:26:16.000
[Amit Varma]: conservatism mean to you? And, you know...

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:22.520
[Guest]: Okay, Burke, you know, is always... Everybody calls himself a Burkean conservatism. Burke

00:26:22.520 --> 00:26:27.280
[Guest]: is always quoted. I even mentioned somewhere in the book that Ambedkar quoted Burke in

00:26:27.280 --> 00:26:35.280
[Guest]: his great speech in our constituent assembly. The reason Burke is fascinating is that he

00:26:35.280 --> 00:26:41.320
[Guest]: called it right on the French Revolution. He said that this is going to result in a

00:26:41.320 --> 00:26:48.520
[Guest]: military dictatorship sooner or later. This is going to result in a permanent hundred

00:26:48.520 --> 00:26:54.680
[Guest]: year wound on the French psyche. You're destroying Notre Dame Cathedral and calling it Temple

00:26:54.680 --> 00:27:01.560
[Guest]: of Reason. You're really making breaks in the continuous change of French culture, going

00:27:01.560 --> 00:27:07.320
[Guest]: back to, you know, French and country of France is more than 1066. English talk 1066. France

00:27:07.320 --> 00:27:13.680
[Guest]: is, I think, 400 AD or something. There's continuity there. And exactly what happened.

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:20.000
[Guest]: You got Napoleon, and you got a military dictatorship, and you got an imperialist war machine. And

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:25.080
[Guest]: the wounds that the French have inflicted on themselves have remained. He called it

00:27:25.080 --> 00:27:30.640
[Guest]: right on the American colonies. Strangely enough, you would think he would... Being

00:27:30.640 --> 00:27:35.280
[Guest]: conservative, he should have opposed their independence. In fact, he took the other position.

00:27:35.280 --> 00:27:40.840
[Guest]: He said these people have left England in order to live as colonists, and we have given

00:27:40.840 --> 00:27:45.800
[Guest]: them charters. Commonwealth of Massachusetts has a charter. Commonwealth of New York has

00:27:45.800 --> 00:27:51.360
[Guest]: a charter. And now you're violating that charter by imposing taxes, by doing stuff. And he

00:27:51.360 --> 00:27:56.760
[Guest]: called it right on India. That I never knew till I read O'Brien. O'Brien has a whole chapter

00:27:56.760 --> 00:28:03.480
[Guest]: on this. Because not everybody knows about Burke's impeachment of Warren Hastings and

00:28:03.480 --> 00:28:11.800
[Guest]: that he was therefore opposed to the perfidies and the excesses and the plunder involved

00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:20.520
[Guest]: in harassing the Begum Zawahud or the Raja Banaras Jait Singh and so on. But the fact

00:28:20.520 --> 00:28:27.800
[Guest]: that Burke had some very concrete ideas on India. First of all, he said this silly thing

00:28:27.800 --> 00:28:35.680
[Guest]: that we can break everything in India and not pay attention to their traditions is ridiculous.

00:28:35.680 --> 00:28:39.800
[Guest]: He said that's a recipe for disaster. And sure enough, that's what happened when we

00:28:39.800 --> 00:28:49.960
[Guest]: had the 1857 uprising when you kind of ignored the traditions of the country. Two, he was

00:28:49.960 --> 00:28:57.080
[Guest]: in favor of directly the House of Commons supervising India. He didn't like this idea

00:28:57.080 --> 00:29:01.600
[Guest]: of the king and the prime minister having a secretary of state for India. And certainly

00:29:01.600 --> 00:29:06.440
[Guest]: he didn't like the idea of a company, East India Company, running a whole country. And

00:29:06.440 --> 00:29:15.040
[Guest]: if that had happened, imagine if you had had five or 10 parliamentary commissioners supervising

00:29:15.040 --> 00:29:20.680
[Guest]: the India office in London. And through them, the governor general here, etc. They would

00:29:20.680 --> 00:29:29.360
[Guest]: have been answerable to local public opinion in England. They would have been on with changes.

00:29:29.360 --> 00:29:34.080
[Guest]: Whereas what happened subsequently in India was an ICS officer would come and stay here

00:29:34.080 --> 00:29:39.520
[Guest]: for 30 years. So he would only be acquainted with the intellectual currents of 30 years

00:29:39.520 --> 00:29:44.600
[Guest]: earlier. He didn't know what was changing or forget intellectual currency, technological,

00:29:44.600 --> 00:29:51.080
[Guest]: any changes that are taking place in the world. So we got a kind of a frozen bureaucracy,

00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:55.040
[Guest]: and one that was very heavy handed, ruled through the secretary of state, which was

00:29:55.040 --> 00:30:00.800
[Guest]: the cabinet office. And George III actually and Pitt opposed Burke because they wanted

00:30:00.800 --> 00:30:04.480
[Guest]: to keep the patronage to themselves. They didn't want to give it over to the parliamentary

00:30:04.480 --> 00:30:10.320
[Guest]: commissioners, which was a pity. So Burke had thought through some of these things,

00:30:10.320 --> 00:30:16.720
[Guest]: even vis-a-vis India, with great patience and with great, you know, kind of intellectual

00:30:16.720 --> 00:30:22.960
[Guest]: agility. So when I read O'Brien, then I went back, and I went to my favorite bookshop in

00:30:22.960 --> 00:30:29.000
[Guest]: New York, Hagersee, and got the complete works of Burke, which I have with me, and started

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:36.080
[Guest]: reading here and there in different bits and pieces. And one started understanding that

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:44.360
[Guest]: this man was not a Bacon or a Locke. He was not a philosopher in that sense. He was more

00:30:44.360 --> 00:30:49.840
[Guest]: of a practical, empirical guy saying, hey, this doesn't make much sense what you're trying

00:30:49.840 --> 00:30:54.600
[Guest]: to do. And this is not a very noble thing that you're trying to do. I mean, that's the

00:30:54.600 --> 00:31:03.760
[Guest]: way he approached discussions. Then when I read Nicholas Philipson's book on Adam Smith,

00:31:03.760 --> 00:31:09.320
[Guest]: I came across a brilliant thing, which I hadn't come across earlier, which was in I think

00:31:09.320 --> 00:31:16.200
[Guest]: Quartly Review or Edinburgh Review, Burke reviewed Adam Smith's theory of moral sentiments,

00:31:16.200 --> 00:31:22.120
[Guest]: book review. And this Philipson quotes extensively, Nicholas Philipson quotes extensively in his

00:31:22.120 --> 00:31:27.600
[Guest]: book. And that's where I came across this expression, wisdom of the swain. You know,

00:31:27.600 --> 00:31:32.260
[Guest]: Burke basically said, hey, common people are wise. This idea that these intellectuals sitting

00:31:32.260 --> 00:31:37.800
[Guest]: in Oxford, Cambridge are wise and common people are stupid or something. And it's a very continental

00:31:37.800 --> 00:31:44.880
[Guest]: idea. The professor in France or Germany has supreme knowledge and the peasants don't know

00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:50.440
[Guest]: anything kind of. It's very much opposed to the Burkean conservative view.

00:31:50.440 --> 00:31:55.680
[Amit Varma]: So, let me try and summarize Burke's central insight and tell me if I've got it right,

00:31:55.680 --> 00:32:00.760
[Amit Varma]: which is, I mean, an insight I more or less agree with, which is that traditions and ways

00:32:00.760 --> 00:32:05.080
[Amit Varma]: of behavior of a place evolve for certain reasons, because they are concomitant with

00:32:05.080 --> 00:32:11.360
[Amit Varma]: human nature, because they reflect what works and what doesn't work. And if we are to make

00:32:11.360 --> 00:32:16.620
[Amit Varma]: a radical shift from this, you know, it causes a violence in society that can lead to trouble

00:32:16.620 --> 00:32:22.480
[Amit Varma]: much as the French Revolution. And therefore, Burke's point is that change is by all means

00:32:22.480 --> 00:32:26.600
[Amit Varma]: good. Let's stick to what's good about the past. Let's discard what is bad about the

00:32:26.600 --> 00:32:32.880
[Amit Varma]: past, but let's change gradually and not cause these fundamental shocks and dislocations.

00:32:32.880 --> 00:32:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And like you sum it up, I'll quote you now from your book, quote, in our view, by which

00:32:37.360 --> 00:32:41.600
[Amit Varma]: you mean in conservatives view, quote, in our view, the principle challenged faced by

00:32:41.600 --> 00:32:46.800
[Amit Varma]: societies is how to change constructively without losing things of value in the process

00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:51.680
[Amit Varma]: of change. Therefore, in principle, we are opposed to revolutionary change, preferring

00:32:51.680 --> 00:32:56.840
[Amit Varma]: the evolutionary variety any day. Correct. That's a that's a correct. This is absolutely

00:32:56.840 --> 00:33:02.240
[Guest]: see the nobody is saying that because there was slavery in the past, we should continue

00:33:02.240 --> 00:33:11.000
[Guest]: with it. Slavery has to go. Now, that is for sure. Or, you know, burda or burning of women

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:17.000
[Guest]: or dowry or whatever. There are there are innumerable things that have to change. The

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:22.720
[Guest]: question is, when you do something abruptly and when you do something wholesale, first

00:33:22.720 --> 00:33:28.520
[Guest]: of all, there's violence, which has unintended consequences, usually which are bad. Very

00:33:28.520 --> 00:33:36.600
[Guest]: rarely does violence have unintended consequences, which are good. Secondly, you lose the good

00:33:36.600 --> 00:33:45.440
[Guest]: things associated with the past. And that's the concern that constantly bothers conservatives

00:33:45.440 --> 00:33:51.600
[Guest]: is that. And that's why it's in my book. Later on, I say it. The best thing that happened

00:33:51.600 --> 00:33:56.600
[Guest]: to us was the way our independence happened. For three years, we actually remained a dominion.

00:33:56.600 --> 00:34:01.820
[Guest]: We didn't even become a republic. We it took place gradually, evolutionary step by step

00:34:01.820 --> 00:34:10.240
[Guest]: by step. It didn't happen. Whereas in 1917 in Russia or 1949 in China, it happened of

00:34:10.240 --> 00:34:17.240
[Guest]: a bitter civil war with with great violence and with a complete rupture with the past.

00:34:17.240 --> 00:34:22.640
[Guest]: You kill off the entire king and his entire royal family in brutal manner and all that

00:34:22.640 --> 00:34:29.120
[Guest]: kind of stuff. It didn't help them in the long run. It actually hurt those societies.

00:34:29.120 --> 00:34:37.880
[Guest]: And by writing our constitution in English, by using the Government of India Act of 1935

00:34:37.880 --> 00:34:45.280
[Guest]: as the basis, by accepting principles of English common law as a basis. Indian Constitution,

00:34:45.280 --> 00:34:50.920
[Guest]: by the way, is the only constitution in the world which has a specific article which allows

00:34:50.920 --> 00:34:58.160
[Guest]: the Supreme Court to intervene in the interests of equity. When the letter of the law doesn't

00:34:58.160 --> 00:35:04.000
[Guest]: achieve equity, the Supreme Court can intervene. Equity is a very basic seven, eight hundred

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:10.160
[Guest]: year old English common law concept. So, we've kept the traditions of the Raj and we've built

00:35:10.160 --> 00:35:15.160
[Guest]: on it. Now, we've changed many things. Now, there are no Rao Bahadurs or Sirs or things

00:35:15.160 --> 00:35:20.080
[Guest]: of the Raj used to give out. I'm not saying we kept everything of the Raj, but we managed

00:35:20.080 --> 00:35:26.720
[Guest]: to do this in an evolutionary step by step constitutional manner where could have approved.

00:35:26.720 --> 00:35:30.200
[Amit Varma]: It could also, of course, be argued that we kept things like the Indian Penal Code with

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:34.400
[Amit Varma]: the sedition law and the anti-free speech laws like 254 and 153A.

00:35:34.400 --> 00:35:41.120
[Guest]: Yeah, the law on homosexuality. I mean, see, the Indian Penal Code is a very... See, one

00:35:41.120 --> 00:35:46.960
[Guest]: of the things I've mentioned somewhere is that... Now, we don't know for a fact whether

00:35:46.960 --> 00:35:54.880
[Guest]: Manusmriti was actually used or it was simply a ideal text that was referred to. But under

00:35:54.880 --> 00:36:01.760
[Guest]: Manusmriti, the same crime committed by persons of different caste origins would have different

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:07.040
[Guest]: punishments. Indian Penal Code doesn't have that. It's quite clear that a murder is a

00:36:07.040 --> 00:36:13.000
[Guest]: murder. It is a crime that is punished and it is not... The cost of the individual is

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:20.000
[Guest]: irrelevant. So, it has those good features. It has features associated with 19th century

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:27.720
[Guest]: social thinking on homosexuality or on sedition which need to change. And I think the way

00:36:27.720 --> 00:36:35.400
[Guest]: to do it again is the way we've done it. Do it by passing a law, having a select committee,

00:36:35.400 --> 00:36:43.320
[Guest]: sit, talk about it, discuss, debate, change the law or go through an elaborate judicial

00:36:43.320 --> 00:36:49.760
[Guest]: process and let the court rule. You know, that's the way to do it, not by having a revolutionary

00:36:49.760 --> 00:36:56.400
[Guest]: change, one fine day saying we will get rid of this. Because then, the whole Penal Code,

00:36:56.400 --> 00:36:59.880
[Guest]: if you throw out, you throw out also some of the good things that are there.

00:36:59.880 --> 00:37:05.600
[Amit Varma]: Right. I'll come back to that a little later. I want to move to another question now, since

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:11.120
[Amit Varma]: we are discussing what conservatism is and what Burke's fundamental insight was. I want

00:37:11.120 --> 00:37:15.640
[Amit Varma]: to quote from someone who is my intellectual hero, Frederick Hayek. And he's written this

00:37:15.640 --> 00:37:20.200
[Amit Varma]: famous essay you must have read called, Why I am not a conservative. So, I'll just quote

00:37:20.200 --> 00:37:23.920
[Amit Varma]: a bit from that. He, of course, at the time called himself a liberal, but that was in

00:37:23.920 --> 00:37:28.280
[Amit Varma]: the classical sense, in the European sense, a classical liberal. Today, he'd be called

00:37:28.280 --> 00:37:33.640
[Amit Varma]: a libertarian and basically both labels, which I think more or less would apply to me to

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:40.280
[Amit Varma]: avoid labels. But here's what Hayek has to say in his essay, Why I am not a conservative.

00:37:40.280 --> 00:37:45.800
[Amit Varma]: Quote, Let me now state what seems to me the decisive objection to any conservatism which

00:37:45.800 --> 00:37:51.160
[Amit Varma]: deserves to be called such. It is that by its very nature, it cannot offer an alternative

00:37:51.160 --> 00:37:56.760
[Amit Varma]: to the direction in which we are moving. It may succeed by its resistance to current tendencies

00:37:56.760 --> 00:38:02.680
[Amit Varma]: in slowing down undesirable developments, but since it does not indicate another direction,

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:07.540
[Amit Varma]: it cannot prevent their continuance. It has for this reason invariably been the fate of

00:38:07.540 --> 00:38:13.600
[Amit Varma]: conservatism to be dragged along a path not of its own choosing. Stop quote. And my question

00:38:13.600 --> 00:38:17.160
[Amit Varma]: here is, I mean, I know what you've clarified multiple times in your book is that conservatives

00:38:17.160 --> 00:38:21.520
[Amit Varma]: don't merely want to stop change. They want to change gradually and they want to keep

00:38:21.520 --> 00:38:25.840
[Amit Varma]: what's best of the past. So, I get that. I'm anticipating that you're going to say that.

00:38:25.840 --> 00:38:32.080
[Amit Varma]: But my deeper sort of question and my genuine puzzlement is that if the central insight

00:38:32.080 --> 00:38:40.480
[Amit Varma]: of conservatism is about the means of affecting change, what about the ends? If I ask a conservative,

00:38:40.480 --> 00:38:45.280
[Amit Varma]: what are your ends? What are they? You know, and you will get different answers from different

00:38:45.280 --> 00:38:50.560
[Amit Varma]: people. You would, of course, also talk about individual rights and so on. But then the

00:38:50.560 --> 00:38:55.960
[Amit Varma]: question is that if conservatism is centered around not changing things abruptly, then

00:38:55.960 --> 00:39:03.160
[Guest]: where do you actually draw your ends from? Okay, let's start with Hayek now. It's a very

00:39:03.160 --> 00:39:12.600
[Guest]: continental view of the world where there's a linear theory of historical progress. And

00:39:12.600 --> 00:39:18.400
[Guest]: so progress is happening and conservatives are being dragged because progress is going

00:39:18.400 --> 00:39:27.920
[Guest]: to happen anyway. Now, we are very, very skeptical about this because this is the thing that

00:39:27.920 --> 00:39:37.480
[Guest]: keeps promising utopia, promising some great progress and therefore don't hold it back,

00:39:37.480 --> 00:39:45.320
[Guest]: which ties up with your question about ends. Actually, conservatives do not have a very

00:39:45.320 --> 00:39:54.640
[Guest]: strong view on ends because we do reject the idea of a utopian end. And we reject the idea

00:39:54.640 --> 00:40:04.120
[Guest]: of perfection. So things will not be perfect. Yes, incrementally, there will be less hunger

00:40:04.120 --> 00:40:12.200
[Guest]: than today. Tomorrow, we hope there will be more freedom for men and women than today.

00:40:12.200 --> 00:40:19.800
[Guest]: Will there be perfect freedom? Will there be an end? Answer is no. So in fact, the means

00:40:19.800 --> 00:40:28.720
[Guest]: are the end. There is no such thing as working towards a superordinate goal that comes at

00:40:28.720 --> 00:40:38.000
[Guest]: the end of the rainbow. That's rejected completely because utopias are the scariest thing for

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:44.160
[Guest]: conservatives because for two reasons. In a consequential sense, most attempts to get

00:40:44.160 --> 00:40:51.220
[Guest]: to utopia lead to dystopias. And that's a fact in history we've seen. In a more fundamental

00:40:51.220 --> 00:40:57.400
[Guest]: moral sense, religious conservatives would take the position that it is not up to human

00:40:57.400 --> 00:41:08.040
[Guest]: beings to make heaven on earth. That is God's role. And non-religious conservatives would

00:41:08.040 --> 00:41:18.960
[Guest]: take the position that such a paradise on earth is neither possible nor feasible and

00:41:18.960 --> 00:41:27.060
[Guest]: its pursuit will only result in hubris. So that would be my response to the Hayek observation

00:41:27.060 --> 00:41:30.560
[Amit Varma]: and your question about ends. That's fair enough. No, I entirely agree with

00:41:30.560 --> 00:41:35.640
[Amit Varma]: you that chasing utopias normally leads to dystopia. But let me sort of try to elaborate

00:41:35.640 --> 00:41:40.920
[Amit Varma]: on where I'm coming from. For me, where I derive my view of the world is not from a

00:41:40.920 --> 00:41:45.440
[Amit Varma]: view of history proceeding in a certain direction or that the world should be like this, a particular

00:41:45.440 --> 00:41:52.000
[Amit Varma]: end state. I rather derive it from a set of values which holds individual rights to be

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:57.160
[Amit Varma]: paramount above all else. And therefore, I want the world to move towards a position

00:41:57.160 --> 00:42:03.520
[Amit Varma]: where the consent of every individual is respected more and there is less and less coercion.

00:42:03.520 --> 00:42:07.800
[Amit Varma]: That's sort of the directional movement that I would like to see.

00:42:07.800 --> 00:42:13.720
[Guest]: We would not agree. You know, for us, the fact is rights and obligations are intertwined.

00:42:13.720 --> 00:42:22.880
[Guest]: The idea that right exists, rights for people exist in isolation of their obligations to

00:42:22.880 --> 00:42:28.040
[Guest]: other human beings, to environment, et cetera, is not something that conservatives would

00:42:28.040 --> 00:42:37.640
[Guest]: easily accept. The second issue really is that things like particularly in the area

00:42:37.640 --> 00:42:47.000
[Guest]: of rights, the in recent times, the liberal position, unfortunately, has moved away beyond

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:52.680
[Guest]: individual rights, to communal rights, to community rights, group rights.

00:42:52.680 --> 00:42:58.000
[Amit Varma]: I think that if I may interrupt that again, I think depends on because the meaning of

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:02.800
[Guest]: the word liberal has been changed and appropriated. Okay, so you're really talking about the left

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:08.680
[Guest]: liberals, non-classical liberals. And that, of course, conservatives are very petrified

00:43:08.680 --> 00:43:13.160
[Guest]: about. No, I opposed it as much as you got. No, I'm telling you why we are petrified about

00:43:13.160 --> 00:43:20.600
[Guest]: because we actually want associative things. We are for associative things. But again,

00:43:20.600 --> 00:43:30.080
[Guest]: from a perspective of common traditions, from a perspective of band of brothers coming together,

00:43:30.080 --> 00:43:42.760
[Guest]: from a perspective of social transactions, trust, the danger with these group rights,

00:43:42.760 --> 00:43:47.160
[Guest]: if you will, is that they become pathological at some stage. And that's what conservatives

00:43:47.160 --> 00:43:58.960
[Guest]: are so scared of. But coming back to your earlier issue, the idea of a right, which

00:43:58.960 --> 00:44:04.960
[Guest]: is not intertwined with an obligation or a duty, it just won't fly with virtually anything.

00:44:04.960 --> 00:44:09.680
[Amit Varma]: Right. So let me respond to both of those. I mean, first, as far as your aversion to

00:44:09.680 --> 00:44:14.520
[Amit Varma]: group rights is concerned, mine is no less, because group rights and individual rights

00:44:14.520 --> 00:44:21.840
[Amit Varma]: can't coexist and group rights always go hand in hand with coercion. But equally, I'm again

00:44:21.840 --> 00:44:27.480
[Amit Varma]: for associative behavior, as long as it is voluntary. Again, that's the consent coercion

00:44:27.480 --> 00:44:33.080
[Amit Varma]: thing. Actually, no sovereign state intervention. As for rights versus obligations, I think

00:44:33.080 --> 00:44:38.040
[Amit Varma]: in the Lockean view of rights, which I subscribe to, I think rights do come with obligations.

00:44:38.040 --> 00:44:44.640
[Amit Varma]: But the only obligation I will accept is the obligation to respect the corresponding rights

00:44:44.640 --> 00:44:50.760
[Amit Varma]: of others. Because only in that situation do your own rights have any meaning. But that

00:44:50.760 --> 00:44:58.160
[Amit Varma]: clarification aside, I don't actually want to harangue you. Because honestly, your book

00:44:58.160 --> 00:45:03.720
[Amit Varma]: was just a wonderful read. I learned a lot from it also about, you know, about the development

00:45:03.720 --> 00:45:07.720
[Amit Varma]: of conservatism in India, things which I didn't know before you showed me a new lens to look

00:45:07.720 --> 00:45:14.120
[Amit Varma]: at it. So I will save my thorny questions for the end, the rest of them. And let's kind

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:21.080
[Amit Varma]: of go back to your book. And an interesting statement you make early in the book is, you

00:45:21.080 --> 00:45:28.160
[Amit Varma]: point out that, quote, conservatism in India is not purely or entirely an imported intellectual

00:45:28.160 --> 00:45:33.120
[Amit Varma]: conceit, you say, quote, its antecedents are both universal and Indian. Two of our civilization's

00:45:33.120 --> 00:45:39.040
[Amit Varma]: foundational text, the Shanti Parva of the Mahabharata and the Tirukkural of Tiruvalluvar

00:45:39.040 --> 00:45:44.080
[Amit Varma]: can be seen as providing the enduring basis of Indian conservatism. And a little later,

00:45:44.080 --> 00:45:50.280
[Amit Varma]: you talk about the Telugu poet Alasi Peddana. And you talk about, yeah, sorry, my bad for

00:45:50.280 --> 00:45:55.800
[Amit Varma]: the pronunciation. And you point out how he quote, dealt with concerns that are uncannily

00:45:55.800 --> 00:46:00.240
[Amit Varma]: similar to those of Scruton today. So elaborate a little bit on that.

00:46:00.240 --> 00:46:10.440
[Guest]: You see, the first of all, the Orientalist view that Indian intellectual traditions are

00:46:10.440 --> 00:46:20.360
[Guest]: ascetic and otherworldly, etc. is comprehensively dismissed, if you look at the Shanti Parva

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:27.120
[Guest]: and the Tirukkural, which I believe both constitute, I use the word foundational texts, very advisedly,

00:46:27.120 --> 00:46:36.800
[Guest]: I believe that they are very, very central to our whole Weltanschauung. They both incidentally

00:46:36.800 --> 00:46:43.520
[Guest]: are interested in the three vargas, the three Purusharthas. In Sanskrit, you would call

00:46:43.520 --> 00:46:51.800
[Guest]: them Artha, Dharma, and Kama. Artha is the pursuit of political and economic activity.

00:46:51.800 --> 00:46:57.480
[Guest]: Dharma is pursuit of virtue and ethics. Kama is a pursuit of pleasure and sensory stuff

00:46:57.480 --> 00:47:05.640
[Guest]: and aesthetic sensibility. It's called Porul Aram and Inmam in Tirukkural. The interesting

00:47:05.640 --> 00:47:12.440
[Guest]: thing that both texts kind of glide over, they acknowledge that the fourth salvation,

00:47:12.440 --> 00:47:18.240
[Guest]: the fourth goal, Moksha, for human beings is the most important and transcends these

00:47:18.240 --> 00:47:24.880
[Guest]: three. But the implicit assumption is you get these three right, salvation is automatically

00:47:24.880 --> 00:47:29.960
[Guest]: taken care of. So, so much for accusing Indians of being otherworldly. Neither is Valluvar

00:47:29.960 --> 00:47:36.200
[Guest]: otherworldly, nor is Vyasa in the Shanti Parva otherworldly. The second thing that they are

00:47:36.200 --> 00:47:45.000
[Guest]: both focused on is how should an individual pursue Artha, Dharma, and Kama, Porul Aram

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:53.400
[Guest]: and Inmam, and how should he or she pursue this in society. So, that's for conservatives,

00:47:53.400 --> 00:48:01.120
[Guest]: the second part is very important. We do not see ourselves as isolated, autonomous people,

00:48:01.120 --> 00:48:10.760
[Guest]: but as people in a band of brothers or sisters. And the focus is in both rights and obligations,

00:48:10.760 --> 00:48:20.200
[Guest]: therefore. The focus is on the sober pursuit of wealth. Sober is as important as pursuit.

00:48:20.200 --> 00:48:29.080
[Guest]: Virtuous pursuit of wealth and political power, and a balanced pursuit of the aesthetic sensibility

00:48:29.080 --> 00:48:37.280
[Guest]: with, imbued with ethics. And then there's extensive discussion on the importance of

00:48:37.280 --> 00:48:41.800
[Guest]: the ploughman in Valluvar. Valluvar, the central figure for Valluvar, by the way, is not the

00:48:41.800 --> 00:48:48.560
[Guest]: merchant or soldier or the king, but it's the ploughman. Because, you know, and I mentioned

00:48:48.560 --> 00:48:56.240
[Guest]: it somewhere, it's almost, it's like, you know, Pierce Ploughman Langman's poem, it's

00:48:56.240 --> 00:49:04.120
[Guest]: almost as if Valluvar anticipates it by a thousand years. The pursuit of activity in

00:49:04.120 --> 00:49:10.840
[Guest]: a meaningful way, and in a social context. Now, in the Shanti Parvat, there's a lot of

00:49:10.840 --> 00:49:22.120
[Guest]: discussion of Rajadharma. What is the appropriate virtuous conduct for a king? So everybody

00:49:22.120 --> 00:49:26.480
[Guest]: says before Magna Carta was written in England, the king was above the law. That was the first

00:49:26.480 --> 00:49:31.600
[Guest]: time that the king was brought under the law. It's not true. Shanti Parvat is quite clear.

00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:39.960
[Guest]: The king is subject to a royal law that he has to follow. Then there is this concern

00:49:39.960 --> 00:49:51.240
[Guest]: about Nyaya, about the fact that you need justice and you need a social milieu in which

00:49:51.240 --> 00:49:56.640
[Guest]: justice and good conduct prevails. For the ancient Indian scholars, the most horrifying

00:49:56.640 --> 00:50:03.040
[Guest]: thought was Matsya Nyaya. Matsya Nyaya is where the big fish eat the small fish. It's

00:50:03.040 --> 00:50:08.880
[Guest]: a breakdown of law and order. It's a breakdown of order in society. For them, that has to

00:50:08.880 --> 00:50:16.960
[Guest]: be the most horrifying times in life. It's like Hobbes, almost, you know, before order

00:50:16.960 --> 00:50:24.980
[Guest]: comes, how it is, how brutish, nasty it is. So this anticipation of so many of these conservative

00:50:24.980 --> 00:50:31.240
[Guest]: ideas going back, and there is one which in fact predates even the Mahabharata and the

00:50:31.240 --> 00:50:36.560
[Guest]: Kural, which goes back all the way to the Apasthma Sutra, the Vajra Veda, which is Yogadharma,

00:50:36.560 --> 00:50:43.120
[Guest]: which comes to your point or Hayek's point about progress. What Yogadharma is an idea

00:50:43.120 --> 00:50:50.440
[Guest]: that different ages have different dharmas. Now, if you were living 2000 years, 3000 years

00:50:50.440 --> 00:50:58.080
[Guest]: ago in ancient Athens, and slavery was prevalent, what would be your advice to a slave? Be an

00:50:58.080 --> 00:51:04.640
[Guest]: obedient slave. Now, that doesn't make it right or wrong or fashionable, but that was

00:51:04.640 --> 00:51:11.180
[Guest]: appropriate for that time. And your advice to the master would be, treat your slave kindly.

00:51:11.180 --> 00:51:16.600
[Guest]: But 2000 years later, you say, no, let's abolish slavery. You know, it's a different, this

00:51:16.600 --> 00:51:24.520
[Guest]: is a different age. In a particular age, in an age before the birth control pill was invented,

00:51:24.520 --> 00:51:30.600
[Guest]: you know, there was a certain level of freedom that women couldn't aspire to. Now, if that

00:51:30.600 --> 00:51:35.880
[Guest]: has changed, if technology provides for certain things, you have to automatically make the

00:51:35.880 --> 00:51:42.520
[Guest]: change that that provides. So, Yogadharma is another one, which is very, very central

00:51:42.520 --> 00:51:47.320
[Guest]: to, particularly to the idea, you know, in Conningsby, which is one of the Israeli's

00:51:47.320 --> 00:51:53.000
[Guest]: famous novels, he mentions that we have to gradually change without abandoning the best

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:58.120
[Guest]: in the past. And that's what Yogadharma is about. There are certain aspects of dharma

00:51:58.120 --> 00:52:05.440
[Guest]: that do not change. You know, right conduct, speaking the truth, those are eternal verities.

00:52:05.440 --> 00:52:10.520
[Guest]: But certain aspects do change, and you must be willing to make. And I think Raja Ram Mohan

00:52:10.520 --> 00:52:16.280
[Guest]: Roy frankly understood that. He understood that, that is why he is such an important

00:52:16.280 --> 00:52:23.720
[Guest]: figure in modern Indian conservatism. He understood that we had to discard some old practices.

00:52:23.720 --> 00:52:27.360
[Guest]: And he did it very cleverly. He simply said, they're not in keeping with the spirit of

00:52:27.360 --> 00:52:34.200
[Guest]: our own scriptures. It's kind of a very clever, dexterous way of doing it. But this Yogadharma

00:52:34.200 --> 00:52:39.800
[Guest]: is also very much there in our texts. Lastly, which is something that we may come back to

00:52:39.800 --> 00:52:46.280
[Guest]: in later discussions, I do pay some attention to the Atharva Veda, where we are, when we

00:52:46.280 --> 00:52:53.520
[Guest]: talk about conserving the environment, which is a very central idea in Indian thought,

00:52:53.520 --> 00:52:59.080
[Guest]: and what it means. In fact, Burke has made a brilliant speech on that subject in the

00:52:59.080 --> 00:53:06.600
[Guest]: House of Commons, not when he was talking about Warren Hastings impeachment, when he

00:53:06.600 --> 00:53:11.560
[Guest]: was talking about the Prince of Arcot's debts. Prince of Arcot's debts are a very funny and

00:53:11.560 --> 00:53:17.440
[Guest]: very sad set of events in Indian history. We can talk about that offline. But anyway,

00:53:17.440 --> 00:53:26.680
[Guest]: while talking about that, Burke refers to the fact that Indian kings built canals, reservoirs,

00:53:26.680 --> 00:53:32.440
[Guest]: created lakes, knowing full well that they would not enjoy them. But they were for the

00:53:32.440 --> 00:53:39.120
[Guest]: enjoyment of future generations. So there was an intergenerational kind of trust and

00:53:39.120 --> 00:53:44.520
[Guest]: transaction there. And Burke talks about it. So he knew enough about India to be able to

00:53:44.520 --> 00:53:47.200
[Amit Varma]: say, to refer to that kind of detail.

00:53:47.200 --> 00:53:51.920
[Amit Varma]: So let's let's sort of come to relatively modern times, by which I mean the last 200

00:53:51.920 --> 00:53:57.880
[Amit Varma]: years or so. And one of the interesting things I sort of discovered in your book was you

00:53:57.880 --> 00:54:03.000
[Amit Varma]: present this lens of looking at Indian conservatism, where you say that it's not one thing. There

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:09.760
[Amit Varma]: are two very distinct strands, which are running through Indian conservatism. And one of them,

00:54:09.760 --> 00:54:15.400
[Amit Varma]: of course, is the Raja Ram Mohan Roy strand, which is sort of more inspired by Burke. Tell

00:54:15.400 --> 00:54:20.560
[Amit Varma]: me a little bit about both these strands. I mean, let's start with Raja Ram Mohan Roy.

00:54:20.560 --> 00:54:27.280
[Guest]: Raja Ram Mohan Roy, one of his most important statements he made to a visiting Frenchman

00:54:27.280 --> 00:54:35.000
[Guest]: was that he wanted British rule to continue for a long time. So here is a man saying something

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:42.240
[Guest]: very important saying, let's not get rid of the British that easily. Let us learn from

00:54:42.240 --> 00:54:49.640
[Guest]: them. Let us imbibe what is good and not be in a hurry for some kind of quick revolutionary

00:54:49.640 --> 00:54:59.040
[Guest]: uprising and change. He would have opposed the 1857 uprising, for instance. And he died

00:54:59.040 --> 00:55:08.400
[Guest]: before that, so we can't say for sure, but I would suspect that he would have. And he

00:55:08.400 --> 00:55:15.640
[Guest]: was also for making sure we maintain continuity with our own traditions. So Upanishads, in

00:55:15.640 --> 00:55:23.720
[Guest]: Brahmo Samaj, he reintroduces or introduces Upanishadic prayers. So he did not see a contradiction

00:55:23.720 --> 00:55:29.240
[Guest]: in getting the best out of the Raj traditions and getting the best out of ancient Indian

00:55:29.240 --> 00:55:38.320
[Guest]: traditions and building on them for constructive, slow, constitutional, evolutionary change.

00:55:38.320 --> 00:55:43.080
[Guest]: How did he ask for change? He wrote a letter to the Governor General. He got signatures.

00:55:43.080 --> 00:55:48.720
[Guest]: He didn't go and, you know, beat up and have a revolutionary attack. No, he petitioned

00:55:48.720 --> 00:55:53.840
[Guest]: in triplicate. Correct. Absolutely. That's I know it sounds boring. It doesn't sound

00:55:53.840 --> 00:56:00.600
[Guest]: romantic. Revolutionaries are always romantic, but this is boring. This is discussions, debates,

00:56:00.600 --> 00:56:09.560
[Guest]: treaties, petitions, signatures. But that's what results in enduring change and in constructive

00:56:09.560 --> 00:56:16.200
[Guest]: change, which does not kind of destroy other stuff while making the change that one wants

00:56:16.200 --> 00:56:21.280
[Guest]: to. He got rid of sati, he got rid of many other things. He was very much in favor of

00:56:21.280 --> 00:56:28.480
[Guest]: English language. Although he was a scholar of Persian Sanskrit, et cetera. He realized

00:56:28.480 --> 00:56:35.720
[Guest]: that in in the Raj, we had this opportunity. And so he wanted English education. So the

00:56:35.720 --> 00:56:49.120
[Guest]: joy represents this bundle of patriotism, pride in the country, pragmatism, empiricism,

00:56:49.120 --> 00:56:58.960
[Guest]: all of the things that we like in and above all, continuity, slow evolutionary, proper

00:56:58.960 --> 00:57:08.920
[Guest]: insightful progress. And I think there is a direct kind of, you know, lying down from

00:57:08.920 --> 00:57:19.120
[Guest]: him to various conservatives right through. And Bhandarkar clearly is in that Yadunath

00:57:19.120 --> 00:57:26.840
[Guest]: Sarkar, is in that league and comes down all the way to Rajagopalachari and Masani in the

00:57:26.840 --> 00:57:31.840
[Guest]: second half of the 20th century. So there is in the political side and frankly, on the

00:57:31.840 --> 00:57:37.480
[Guest]: aesthetic side, there is also with with it coming down through Kumaraswamy and so on.

00:57:37.480 --> 00:57:46.160
[Guest]: This idea that we need to keep this balance between the Upanishads and modern learning.

00:57:46.160 --> 00:57:51.600
[Guest]: It's not one or the other, you know, many, many people felt it was one or the other.

00:57:51.600 --> 00:58:00.620
[Guest]: In fact, I've argued that instead of decrying English and accusing English speaking Indians

00:58:00.620 --> 00:58:06.640
[Guest]: of being Macaulay Putras and so on, we should look at Macaulay, who was actually fairly

00:58:06.640 --> 00:58:13.120
[Guest]: vain and conceited and foolish fellow in many other respects. But he did us a favor. It's

00:58:13.120 --> 00:58:18.200
[Guest]: the way we should look at it. Like Hrishyashringa, I don't know if you remember in Valmiki Ramayana,

00:58:18.200 --> 00:58:25.200
[Guest]: he's the man who does the yajna and Rama is born. So he gave us the great prince of our

00:58:25.200 --> 00:58:30.640
[Guest]: land Rama. So similarly, Macaulay, for whatever stupid reasons of his own, has given us this

00:58:30.640 --> 00:58:36.480
[Guest]: great gift of English, which instead of kind of getting het up and worked up about and

00:58:36.480 --> 00:58:42.400
[Guest]: having an inferiority complex about, we need to understand its value. And we need to see

00:58:42.400 --> 00:58:46.000
[Guest]: it as part of the continuity. There is no discontinuity there.

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:50.320
[Amit Varma]: I would say English has been an Indian language for more than a century now. I did an episode

00:58:50.320 --> 00:58:54.380
[Amit Varma]: with the historian Manu Pillay and he pointed out how when the Indian National Congress

00:58:54.380 --> 00:59:00.680
[Amit Varma]: met for the first time in 1886 or whatever year it was, 1885, that, you know, people

00:59:00.680 --> 00:59:04.400
[Amit Varma]: came from all over, they were dressed in all kinds of clothes, but the one common thing,

00:59:04.400 --> 00:59:08.160
[Amit Varma]: the one condition practically for being part of the gathering is that you knew English,

00:59:08.160 --> 00:59:12.560
[Amit Varma]: otherwise, how would you converse? So it was almost as if the British gave us that common

00:59:12.560 --> 00:59:16.960
[Amit Varma]: thread. I want to come back to exploring in much more detail the Raja Ram Mohan Roy strand

00:59:16.960 --> 00:59:20.880
[Amit Varma]: as it were, but for the benefit of our listeners, before we come back to that, can you also

00:59:20.880 --> 00:59:23.920
[Guest]: talk a little bit about the second strand and what it is, which is about

00:59:23.920 --> 00:59:30.600
[Guest]: There is a second strand in Indian conservatism and most leftists do not like to admit it

00:59:30.600 --> 00:59:36.440
[Guest]: or do not, or I think just by, they feel that just by dismissing it, it will go away or

00:59:36.440 --> 00:59:42.360
[Guest]: it will get less, it will become intellectually lightweight, and I reject that. I think it

00:59:42.360 --> 00:59:48.160
[Guest]: is a very respectable school. You may have agreements, disagreements with it, but it's

00:59:48.160 --> 00:59:55.600
[Guest]: worthy of respect, it's worthy of interest, it's worthy of study, which is the Hindu nationalist

00:59:55.600 --> 01:00:06.040
[Guest]: school of Indian conservatism, which starts with, in some sense, that may be earlier anti-Semites,

01:00:06.040 --> 01:00:15.920
[Guest]: but at modern times, it starts with Bankimchandra Chatterjee. And it has its own lineage going

01:00:15.920 --> 01:00:23.840
[Guest]: down through Lajpatrai, Malavya, even again, Banarkar is here also, you can see him on

01:00:23.840 --> 01:00:29.920
[Guest]: both sides here. And then it comes down all the way to Dindayal Upadhyay, Shyamprasad

01:00:29.920 --> 01:00:36.920
[Guest]: Mukherjee. So that has got its own intellectual gravitas. And the argument will always be

01:00:36.920 --> 01:00:45.320
[Guest]: made whether this is in fact conservative, or is it a radical revivalist school. And

01:00:45.320 --> 01:00:50.960
[Guest]: I think I have taken the position and I continue to take the position that it is either a subset

01:00:50.960 --> 01:00:57.200
[Guest]: of Indian conservatism, or it's a sibling of Burkean Indian conservatism. It is not

01:00:57.200 --> 01:01:05.720
[Guest]: something far removed. It's very much there. And just kind of ad hominem attacks or just

01:01:05.720 --> 01:01:11.040
[Guest]: kind of glib dismissals is not going to make its intellectual respectability go away.

01:01:11.040 --> 01:01:16.640
[Amit Varma]: I think I have to confess that I used to glibly dismiss it myself as well. And it's actually

01:01:16.640 --> 01:01:20.960
[Amit Varma]: in the course of doing this podcast and many episodes, such as a recent episode with Akshay

01:01:20.960 --> 01:01:24.480
[Amit Varma]: Mukul, where we spoke about the Gita Press, when we realized that it's actually a very

01:01:24.480 --> 01:01:30.080
[Amit Varma]: coherent intellectual tradition with its own values and first principles, which I may not

01:01:30.080 --> 01:01:34.240
[Amit Varma]: agree with. But that doesn't mean that, you know, one should not engage with it and that

01:01:34.240 --> 01:01:39.520
[Amit Varma]: it is nothing but bigotry and misogyny dressed up in more respectable colors, which is what

01:01:39.520 --> 01:01:44.600
[Amit Varma]: I once used to think. And I have a more nuanced view of that now. And of course, Mota Mota,

01:01:44.600 --> 01:01:50.160
[Amit Varma]: the one point that you make in your book is that the Raja Ram Mohan Roy strand of Indian

01:01:50.160 --> 01:01:55.160
[Amit Varma]: conservatism sort of became sort of lost its impetus around the death of the Swatantra

01:01:55.160 --> 01:02:00.080
[Amit Varma]: Party. And the conservatism that you now see with Hindu nationalism is really a form of

01:02:00.080 --> 01:02:01.080
[Amit Varma]: the Bankim Chandra Chottapadhyay.

01:02:01.080 --> 01:02:03.600
[Guest]: At least in the political sphere, you're right.

01:02:03.600 --> 01:02:04.600
[Amit Varma]: At least in the political sphere.

01:02:04.600 --> 01:02:11.640
[Guest]: Yes, that is correct. I think I think Burkean conservatism today would not be able to operate

01:02:11.640 --> 01:02:18.200
[Guest]: as an independent political movement. Its best hope is to try and influence other movements.

01:02:18.200 --> 01:02:23.080
[Amit Varma]: So I'd like to go back to your book now in your chapter on conservatism in the political

01:02:23.080 --> 01:02:28.640
[Amit Varma]: sphere in India, you have a sort of a fascinating chronology of this tradition, the Burkean

01:02:28.640 --> 01:02:33.360
[Amit Varma]: tradition, the Raja Ram Mohan Roy tradition. And one of the interesting points that you

01:02:33.360 --> 01:02:39.400
[Amit Varma]: make there is their willingness to work with and often their support for the British and

01:02:39.400 --> 01:02:44.600
[Amit Varma]: often for good reasons that liberals today would appreciate. For example, you know, again

01:02:44.600 --> 01:02:48.680
[Amit Varma]: to quote from your book at one point you say, quote, the historian Rajmohan Gandhi has pointed

01:02:48.680 --> 01:02:54.400
[Amit Varma]: out that the Dalit leader Anshus had gone one step further when in as early as 1970,

01:02:54.400 --> 01:02:59.320
[Amit Varma]: he had argued that the departure of the British in the launch of home rule, whether by Brahmins

01:02:59.320 --> 01:03:05.240
[Amit Varma]: or non Brahmins, would crush the Dalits. Stop quote and later on you write, quote, the Raj

01:03:05.240 --> 01:03:10.920
[Amit Varma]: did have a liberating touch for India's downtrodden for reasons of their own persons as distinct

01:03:10.920 --> 01:03:15.880
[Amit Varma]: as Bhera Malabari, Pandita Ramabai, Cornelia Swarabji, and others were also supporters

01:03:15.880 --> 01:03:20.760
[Amit Varma]: of prolonged British rule. They believed that it prevented the emergence of a ruling elite

01:03:20.760 --> 01:03:27.040
[Amit Varma]: dominated by the upper caste. And later on in the book, you say, quote, the same issue

01:03:27.040 --> 01:03:32.520
[Amit Varma]: received considerable attention from our detractors like Kipling, who argued that Indians did

01:03:32.520 --> 01:03:37.840
[Amit Varma]: not deserve freedom, principally, because we were given to oppressing our women and

01:03:37.840 --> 01:03:43.160
[Amit Varma]: our poor. And in fact, it was a British who protected these unhappy residents of our fair

01:03:43.160 --> 01:03:50.120
[Amit Varma]: land. Stop quote. And, you know, it also strikes me that I've been reading biographies of Churchill

01:03:50.120 --> 01:03:54.640
[Amit Varma]: recently, because I've been sort of researching the Bengal famine. And the interesting thing

01:03:54.640 --> 01:03:59.600
[Amit Varma]: is that a lot of Churchill's criticisms of Gandhi in the Congress, you know, they make

01:03:59.600 --> 01:04:03.400
[Amit Varma]: for pithy quotes, but when you look at his elaborations for them, they have to do with

01:04:03.400 --> 01:04:08.240
[Amit Varma]: all these upper caste, we know how they treat the Dalits, or the lower caste, as he would

01:04:08.240 --> 01:04:13.240
[Amit Varma]: call them. And, you know, if we leave India, God knows what will happen to them. And this

01:04:13.240 --> 01:04:18.280
[Amit Varma]: is very interesting, because, like, on the whole, I think that empire hurt us much more

01:04:18.280 --> 01:04:24.160
[Amit Varma]: than it helped us. And one can argue that, but it is not a complete black and white situation.

01:04:24.160 --> 01:04:29.880
[Amit Varma]: And the leaders of that generation possibly could not know what we now know with the benefit

01:04:29.880 --> 01:04:35.520
[Amit Varma]: of hindsight, that this can be a viable independent nation. They just knew sort of what the reality

01:04:35.520 --> 01:04:40.040
[Amit Varma]: is, which is that the British are ruling, how best do we work to make things within

01:04:40.040 --> 01:04:42.160
[Amit Varma]: that tradition? That's a classic conservative thinking.

01:04:42.160 --> 01:04:47.880
[Guest]: No, I think within the British establishment, while there were some who believed that there

01:04:47.880 --> 01:04:55.280
[Guest]: could never be a viable, free India, even early on, Malcolm and Montserrat Elphinstone

01:04:55.280 --> 01:05:01.600
[Guest]: and Monroe had kind of figured out that eventually, British rule would end and Indians would take

01:05:01.600 --> 01:05:10.960
[Guest]: on. The question really is that, my point is, in the NCERT textbooks, post-independence,

01:05:10.960 --> 01:05:17.200
[Guest]: anyone who supported British rule is portrayed as a traitor, as a bad person. And I'm saying

01:05:17.200 --> 01:05:26.000
[Guest]: there's such a bloody range of people. Malabaria, Jyotiba Phule, I mean, Anchar Sahej, Ambedkar,

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:29.520
[Guest]: Tej Bahadur Sapoor, they're not all, they're quite patriotic.

01:05:29.520 --> 01:05:30.520
[Amit Varma]: Gopi Lalade.

01:05:30.520 --> 01:05:37.640
[Guest]: They were not, they were quite patriotic. And the point is that, they were not, and

01:05:37.640 --> 01:05:42.720
[Guest]: of course, these leftists will say, Compradors, all the rubbish words they use. They don't

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:50.160
[Guest]: change the fact that the, I mentioned earlier, technically, I don't know how many kings in

01:05:50.160 --> 01:05:58.520
[Guest]: India actually use the Manusmriti, but technically, a Dalit's rights in a criminal court were

01:05:58.520 --> 01:06:04.440
[Guest]: far fewer than an upper caste person's rights in, under the Manusmriti. And this was not

01:06:04.440 --> 01:06:09.640
[Guest]: the case with the Indian penal court, which Macaulay wrote. So, there is a goodness that

01:06:09.640 --> 01:06:15.920
[Guest]: the British rule had towards certain subaltern groups. And this granular study needs to be

01:06:15.920 --> 01:06:23.080
[Guest]: made. You need to listen to them. It's not just NCERT telling us British rule was bad.

01:06:23.080 --> 01:06:27.040
[Guest]: What did Anchar say? What did, you know, what did Ambedkar say? Ambedkar was a member of

01:06:27.040 --> 01:06:31.200
[Guest]: the Vice-President's Executive Council right through the war. Does that make him any less

01:06:31.200 --> 01:06:38.000
[Guest]: patriotic? I mean, of course not. Hindu Mahasabha President made speeches encouraging Indians

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:44.120
[Guest]: to join the, the war effort, because he said, for so long, we've been disarmed, and we haven't

01:06:44.120 --> 01:06:48.960
[Guest]: been given military training. Let us join the Navy, Air Force and Army. Was that unpatriotic?

01:06:48.960 --> 01:06:54.960
[Guest]: I think Mahatma Gandhi did during the First World War, right? He did. So, does that make

01:06:54.960 --> 01:07:05.040
[Guest]: them unpatriotic? You know, in fact, in these, these things, easy ways of describing dismissing

01:07:05.040 --> 01:07:13.000
[Guest]: people take away from the, the complex relationship between the British and the Indians. Most

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:22.520
[Guest]: Indian soldiers who joined the British Indian Army saw soldiering as a noble profession,

01:07:22.520 --> 01:07:27.480
[Guest]: as something that they were proud to do, and they went and did it. Now, you can't dismiss

01:07:27.480 --> 01:07:32.120
[Guest]: them as mercenary, unpatriotic people. In fact, the present government at least has

01:07:32.120 --> 01:07:39.400
[Guest]: made you know, I've written in the book, with Belgium, with Britain, with France, with Israel,

01:07:39.400 --> 01:07:46.280
[Guest]: we have now honoured Indian soldiers. Otherwise, the previous dispensations from 47 onwards,

01:07:46.280 --> 01:07:50.880
[Guest]: you wanted to keep quiet about the Indian contribution to First World War and Second

01:07:50.880 --> 01:07:54.480
[Amit Varma]: World War. And all of those soldiers were fighting for the government of India as it

01:07:54.480 --> 01:07:58.920
[Amit Varma]: was then. It's just a different matter that it was a part of the empire. But they might

01:07:58.920 --> 01:08:03.560
[Guest]: have been fighting for their regiment, which is very important for them. I mean, this,

01:08:03.560 --> 01:08:12.200
[Guest]: this exposed fact to judgment by these self appointed judges, I find that very, very difficult

01:08:12.200 --> 01:08:17.620
[Guest]: to accept the Madras regiment, which is the oldest regiment of the Indian Army started

01:08:17.620 --> 01:08:22.880
[Guest]: by Stringer Lawrence around the siege of our court in 1750. Now, what are we talking about?

01:08:22.880 --> 01:08:29.080
[Guest]: It had Hindus, Muslims, Christians, it had Dalit supper castes, it was one of the first

01:08:29.080 --> 01:08:37.000
[Guest]: integrated institutions in India. Now, that is a British gift to us. Now, you can say

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:42.680
[Guest]: they did many other bad things, they had famines, they had racist courts, they didn't let us

01:08:42.680 --> 01:08:47.240
[Guest]: sit in first class. I'm not saying everything that they did was right. But you must say

