[Amit Varma]: of this book was the two parallel strands of Indian conservatism, which, you know, I

01:10:56.680 --> 01:11:00.800
[Amit Varma]: am roughly taking the liberty of calling them the Raja Ram Mohan Roy strand and the Bankim

01:11:00.800 --> 01:11:05.560
[Amit Varma]: Chandra Chottopadhyay strand. That's a perfectly correct way of looking at it. 3R and BCC.

01:11:05.560 --> 01:11:11.440
[Amit Varma]: That's to even shorten it further. So I want to now sort of, you know, you've referred

01:11:11.440 --> 01:11:15.840
[Amit Varma]: to RG Bhandarkar a couple of times and you've referred to his 1895 speech. So I'll just

01:11:15.840 --> 01:11:16.840
[Guest]: quote from that.

01:11:16.840 --> 01:11:19.680
[Amit Varma]: Please, what a brilliant sentence.

01:11:19.680 --> 01:11:25.520
[Amit Varma]: And that seems to encapsulate the sort of Burkean conservatism that, you know, a lot

01:11:25.520 --> 01:11:30.440
[Amit Varma]: of the Indian liberals slash conservatives of the time, and I'll come to that nomenclature

01:11:30.440 --> 01:11:36.840
[Amit Varma]: as well, used to believe in. And Mr. Bhandarkar says, this is 1895, mind you, quote, we should

01:11:36.840 --> 01:11:41.960
[Amit Varma]: not adopt the procedure of the French Revolution, but imitate the mode of action of the English

01:11:41.960 --> 01:11:47.920
[Amit Varma]: people whose pupils we are. They have realized as great changes as the French Revolution

01:11:47.920 --> 01:11:53.000
[Amit Varma]: sought to affect, but in a manner which connects them with the past history of the country,

01:11:53.000 --> 01:11:58.800
[Amit Varma]: stop quote, and you speak about this sentence, your words now, quote, this single statement

01:11:58.800 --> 01:12:03.960
[Amit Varma]: can be considered the high watermark of 19th and early 20th century conservatism. And you

01:12:03.960 --> 01:12:09.200
[Amit Varma]: know, some of my intellectual heroes are people I've thought of as liberal heroes in the classical

01:12:09.200 --> 01:12:15.800
[Amit Varma]: liberal sense, people like Naoroji, Ranade, Gopal Krishna Gokhale, especially Agarkar.

01:12:15.800 --> 01:12:20.840
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that in your book, you have appropriated them all. And where I guess

01:12:20.840 --> 01:12:25.480
[Amit Varma]: it fits in is that it seems to me that in their belief for gradualism working within

01:12:25.480 --> 01:12:30.360
[Amit Varma]: the system, giving petitions in triplicate, what they are doing is moving towards what

01:12:30.360 --> 01:12:33.960
[Amit Varma]: I would call liberal ends through conservative means.

01:12:33.960 --> 01:12:42.760
[Guest]: Well, I would say they are advocating gradual, constructive, evolutionary change. That's

01:12:42.760 --> 01:12:47.920
[Guest]: the way I would put it. Because as I said, as we talked earlier, this ends always worries

01:12:47.920 --> 01:12:56.000
[Guest]: us. And I think the reason I've also mentioned why many of these people did not get tracked

01:12:56.000 --> 01:13:05.840
[Guest]: as conservatives. I laid the blame entirely with a section of stupid Tories in England,

01:13:05.840 --> 01:13:16.440
[Guest]: who represent the George III Lord North School of Tories and going back to the 1760s, 1770s.

01:13:16.440 --> 01:13:23.800
[Guest]: And which also had an element of racism about it. So Naoroji could only get election ticket

01:13:23.800 --> 01:13:30.200
[Guest]: from the Liberal Party. You know, when Gokhale went to England, only liberals would meet

01:13:30.200 --> 01:13:36.800
[Guest]: to listen to him. So the Tories cut themselves off from the spirit of gradual change when

01:13:36.800 --> 01:13:43.080
[Guest]: it came to India. Not all Tories, but most Tories did. And that is what Burke would have

01:13:43.080 --> 01:13:49.080
[Guest]: emphasized, did in fact, emphasize in his speeches. And that's what they lost out on.

01:13:49.080 --> 01:13:56.160
[Guest]: As a result, willy nilly, all these guys got associated with the British Liberal Party

01:13:56.160 --> 01:14:03.920
[Guest]: and therefore they got tagged along as liberals. And yes, the question of what is liberal and

01:14:03.920 --> 01:14:09.720
[Guest]: what is conservatives. I mean, considering we are now talking about intellectual traditions

01:14:09.720 --> 01:14:15.560
[Guest]: which are 300 years old, it's not some hoary antiquity going back to Plato or Isaiah. This

01:14:15.560 --> 01:14:23.000
[Guest]: is recent times. And during the times of Burke and in the times of Locke and Adam Smith and

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:31.400
[Guest]: so on, these were still evolving terms. Okay. And so too in India, I think they were evolving

01:14:31.400 --> 01:14:38.480
[Guest]: terms. Now what Bandarkar is saying is very key. He's saying several things in that statement.

01:14:38.480 --> 01:14:45.000
[Guest]: He's saying one, the British achieved the same change that the French achieved. Right.

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:51.720
[Guest]: Liberty before law, extended franchise, all those things that were, that the French Revolution

01:14:51.720 --> 01:14:59.800
[Guest]: gave as gifts to its citizens. But they achieved it without the violence. And more importantly,

01:14:59.800 --> 01:15:06.400
[Guest]: they achieved it without a break in their history, in their consciousness. So, there

01:15:06.400 --> 01:15:13.500
[Guest]: remained the continuing thread of Englishness, which was violently disrupted in France and

01:15:13.500 --> 01:15:19.240
[Guest]: frankly till the 20th century, till the Dreyfus case and so on. France never really recovered

01:15:19.240 --> 01:15:24.800
[Guest]: from these traditions of anti-clericalism at one extreme, Roman Catholic conservatism,

01:15:24.800 --> 01:15:30.180
[Guest]: monarchism, all kinds of things. They just never managed to create a blended blend of

01:15:30.180 --> 01:15:37.000
[Guest]: brothers the way the English were able to do. That's what he's trying to say that, hey,

01:15:37.000 --> 01:15:42.200
[Guest]: let's imitate the British. Let's take our traditions along. The other important point

01:15:42.200 --> 01:15:50.000
[Guest]: he's making, which is subtly inserted there, we are their pupils after all. So, there he's

01:15:50.000 --> 01:15:55.400
[Guest]: making the point that we have a large connection. We are being ruled by them. That connection

01:15:55.400 --> 01:16:00.300
[Guest]: is there. It's an organic connection. It's a link. It's the contingencies of history

01:16:00.300 --> 01:16:06.080
[Guest]: have done it. If Iyer Coote had lost at Wandiwash, the French might have ruled us. I mean, these

01:16:06.080 --> 01:16:10.660
[Guest]: are contingencies in history. And we never know how the count of actuals would have been.

01:16:10.660 --> 01:16:16.320
[Guest]: But given that it has happened, what Bandarkar is saying, we are their pupils and we should

01:16:16.320 --> 01:16:22.600
[Guest]: learn from them. We should take advantage of British rule. We should obviously work

01:16:22.600 --> 01:16:27.100
[Guest]: against those things about British rule which are bad or inimical to our interests. Nobody

01:16:27.100 --> 01:16:34.800
[Guest]: is denying that. Naroji never denied that. He was very clear about that. But do it while

01:16:34.800 --> 01:16:38.880
[Guest]: not jettisoning the good things about British rule.

01:16:38.880 --> 01:16:44.200
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing is that even Gandhi himself was of the school of thought. He was

01:16:44.200 --> 01:16:48.440
[Amit Varma]: a great admirer of Gokhale in South Africa. He would basically be petitioning by triplicate

01:16:48.440 --> 01:16:49.440
[Guest]: till he did his first satyagraha.

01:16:49.440 --> 01:16:54.280
[Guest]: He never started a satyagraha without first giving a petition, by the way. Not one. First

01:16:54.280 --> 01:17:00.320
[Guest]: he would write a petition request to Irwin, to anybody. It didn't matter who. Only then

01:17:00.320 --> 01:17:02.560
[Guest]: would he start his first satyagraha.

01:17:02.560 --> 01:17:08.960
[Amit Varma]: And it just strikes me that, you know, just thinking of Gandhi's dandi march, Naroji in

01:17:08.960 --> 01:17:13.280
[Amit Varma]: 1894 or 1895, if I remember correctly, had brought up the salt tax in the British Parliament,

01:17:13.280 --> 01:17:18.200
[Amit Varma]: demanding that it be repealed. And Gandhi took up the same cause later. And the irony

01:17:18.200 --> 01:17:22.440
[Amit Varma]: is both of them failed because the salt tax today is far higher, no matter how you look

01:17:22.440 --> 01:17:24.080
[Amit Varma]: at it, than it was back in the day.

01:17:24.080 --> 01:17:28.760
[Guest]: Is salt subject to GST? I don't think so. Is it?

01:17:28.760 --> 01:17:32.680
[Amit Varma]: I don't know. But the last I checked, like three years ago, I wrote a piece about it.

01:17:32.680 --> 01:17:38.080
[Amit Varma]: And the last I checked, the salt tax in independent India was much more than under the British,

01:17:38.080 --> 01:17:42.480
[Guest]: which, in a sense, buttresses my point of the kind of tragedy, the kind of oppression

01:17:42.480 --> 01:17:49.360
[Guest]: you should get this in the front pages, because this is something we, we must be the problem

01:17:49.360 --> 01:17:56.720
[Guest]: with salt in the British was more than the tax. It was also an egregiously absurd monopoly.

01:17:56.720 --> 01:18:01.840
[Guest]: And in fact, there are studies which show that it might have actually resulted in lower

01:18:01.840 --> 01:18:07.760
[Guest]: consumption of salt among the poor, stunting of bodies and all kinds of, you know, really

01:18:07.760 --> 01:18:14.480
[Guest]: reprehensible consequences. There was a department called Akbari department. Akbari department

01:18:14.480 --> 01:18:22.080
[Guest]: was, and people got jobs in Akbari department, they, they sold salt and controlled salt.

01:18:22.080 --> 01:18:28.120
[Guest]: There's a Premchand short story called Namakka Daroga. So there is a Daroga, there is a policeman

01:18:28.120 --> 01:18:35.080
[Guest]: or a police inspector whose job is to control salt, Namakka Daroga. So it was a very central

01:18:35.080 --> 01:18:38.120
[Guest]: part of the Raj experience and a very unfortunate one.

01:18:38.120 --> 01:18:43.360
[Amit Varma]: Which is a nice segue to sort of the next point I want to look at, which is conservative

01:18:43.360 --> 01:18:47.560
[Amit Varma]: support for markets. Because the interesting thing is the British also, for example, destroyed

01:18:47.560 --> 01:18:52.480
[Amit Varma]: the cotton industry in India, and it, you know, all sort of shifted to Manchester and

01:18:52.480 --> 01:18:58.760
[Amit Varma]: they destroyed many local industries. And but what a mistake that people often make

01:18:58.760 --> 01:19:05.840
[Amit Varma]: today is conflating empire and markets, just because empire came to us via a corporation,

01:19:05.840 --> 01:19:11.560
[Amit Varma]: which is the East India Company. But as many of what I would call the great freedom fighting

01:19:11.560 --> 01:19:16.320
[Amit Varma]: liberals, but you would say conservatives, and I think there's, you know, sense in ascribing

01:19:16.320 --> 01:19:21.680
[Amit Varma]: both those labels to them. What a lot of them constantly protested about was what the British

01:19:21.680 --> 01:19:26.600
[Amit Varma]: really did was they came here and they destroyed free markets in India, rather than the other

01:19:26.600 --> 01:19:32.000
[Amit Varma]: way around. And I'm again going to quote from your book, quote, both Naoroji and Dutt, that's

01:19:32.000 --> 01:19:37.040
[Amit Varma]: Dadabhai Naoroji and R C Dutt, both Naoroji and Dutt held firm that the Indian entrepreneur,

01:19:37.040 --> 01:19:42.280
[Amit Varma]: the Indian merchant, the Indian producer did not need or want any special support. What

01:19:42.280 --> 01:19:46.800
[Amit Varma]: they advocated was a free and level playing field, where British economic interests and

01:19:46.800 --> 01:19:53.240
[Amit Varma]: the interests of favored British crony capitalists would not be the deciding factor in the framing

01:19:53.240 --> 01:19:58.600
[Amit Varma]: of government policies and actions, stop quote. And they were, of course, protesting behavior,

01:19:58.600 --> 01:20:03.000
[Amit Varma]: which impoverished millions in our country, which destroyed our local economy, and which

01:20:03.000 --> 01:20:07.640
[Amit Varma]: even other great conservatives like Burke and Adam Smith protested against. Adam Smith

01:20:07.640 --> 01:20:13.440
[Guest]: hated the East India Company for two reasons. One, he felt that it is ridiculous to allow

01:20:13.440 --> 01:20:19.360
[Guest]: a commercial company to rule a country. It will always rule in the interest of its shareholders,

01:20:19.360 --> 01:20:24.600
[Guest]: not of the country, which is the primary purpose of government, to rule for the benefit of

01:20:24.600 --> 01:20:32.680
[Guest]: the citizens. And two, because it was a monopoly. On both counts, he hated it. Burke, of course,

01:20:32.680 --> 01:20:38.680
[Guest]: liked it immensely, for very similar reasons. I think the Valsal Neerajan actually made

01:20:38.680 --> 01:20:44.360
[Guest]: this point in practical terms when he fought with the British shipping companies, P&O,

01:20:44.360 --> 01:20:48.960
[Guest]: whatever the shipping company was, Inchcape, Lord Inchcape was a guy running it. You know,

01:20:48.960 --> 01:20:49.960
[Guest]: they basically had monopolies.

01:20:49.960 --> 01:20:50.960
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:20:50.960 --> 01:20:55.480
[Guest]: And he said, wait a minute, I don't want to run a ship. What's the big deal? You know,

01:20:55.480 --> 01:21:02.040
[Guest]: in fact, there is a very famous Tamilian, V.O. Chidambaram Pillai. He started a South

01:21:02.040 --> 01:21:05.920
[Guest]: Indian shipping, steam shipping company, and he was basically put in jail. He was not allowed

01:21:05.920 --> 01:21:14.480
[Guest]: to, I mean, we were not, free entry, which is one of the requirements of a market economy,

01:21:14.480 --> 01:21:15.480
[Guest]: was he essentially denied.

01:21:15.480 --> 01:21:19.240
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I did an episode on the historian Manu Pillai about this and he mentioned Mr.

01:21:19.240 --> 01:21:28.040
[Amit Varma]: Pillai, and who started this thing in about, I think 1906, 1907, lost everything, was impoverished.

01:21:28.040 --> 01:21:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And then when Gandhi returned to India from South Africa, he was this one time tycoon

01:21:33.000 --> 01:21:39.760
[Amit Varma]: was in the egregious position of trying to borrow a little bit of a petty amount from

01:21:39.760 --> 01:21:45.200
[Amit Varma]: Mohandas Gandhi and just makes you feel so sad that these sort of forgotten heroes and

01:21:45.200 --> 01:21:50.320
[Amit Varma]: the way they were destroyed by an oppressive empire, not entirely dissimilar from the oppressive

01:21:50.320 --> 01:21:51.320
[Amit Varma]: empire of today.

01:21:51.320 --> 01:21:58.160
[Guest]: Yeah, this is the point, you know, when state sovereign governments decide to use their

01:21:58.160 --> 01:22:05.160
[Guest]: power to stifle markets, to stifle free human economic activity, they invariably do it to

01:22:05.160 --> 01:22:13.080
[Guest]: help one bunch of people who support them. And the rest is history, rest is sadness.

01:22:13.080 --> 01:22:19.480
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's sad that the intellectual argument for markets becomes hard to make an almost

01:22:19.480 --> 01:22:23.600
[Amit Varma]: counterintuitive because what people from the outside is they see companies benefit

01:22:23.600 --> 01:22:28.160
[Amit Varma]: and they conflate that with markets. So earlier, you would look at East India Company benefiting

01:22:28.160 --> 01:22:32.120
[Amit Varma]: and you would conflate that with, oh, look what free markets have done to India when

01:22:32.120 --> 01:22:36.280
[Amit Varma]: in reality, there was only cronyism, no free markets. And you have a similar thing today

01:22:36.280 --> 01:22:40.880
[Amit Varma]: when you have that, oh, look at the favours the government is dispensing to its favoured

01:22:40.880 --> 01:22:45.640
[Amit Varma]: capitalists be they Ambani, Adani, whoever. And again, this is cronyism. It's not free

01:22:45.640 --> 01:22:53.440
[Guest]: markets. We don't have free markets here either. Free entry is one of the most important things.

01:22:53.440 --> 01:22:58.840
[Guest]: Anybody should be able to enter a business, you know, there's licensing, there's prohibiting

01:22:58.840 --> 01:23:07.160
[Guest]: people from entering business, giving entire Russian trade goes to one British company,

01:23:07.160 --> 01:23:11.240
[Guest]: entire Indian trade one company. Absurd, completely absurd.

01:23:11.240 --> 01:23:13.800
[Amit Varma]: So I'll take you now to something again, which you said in your book, you just brought up

01:23:13.800 --> 01:23:18.160
[Amit Varma]: George the third, and you pointed out in your book, and this is very interesting that in

01:23:18.160 --> 01:23:22.520
[Amit Varma]: some ways, there is a similarity between George the third and Churchill, in the sense that

01:23:22.520 --> 01:23:28.640
[Amit Varma]: in the 1930s, one of the aims of all these Indian conservatives was actually about to

01:23:28.640 --> 01:23:34.600
[Amit Varma]: happen. India was about to be granted dominion status as Stanley Baldwin wanted and Baldwin

01:23:34.600 --> 01:23:39.280
[Amit Varma]: was firm about it. But Churchill staked his career on it. In fact, that decade of his

01:23:39.280 --> 01:23:44.440
[Amit Varma]: is called the wilderness years because he chose to go against his party on two questions.

01:23:44.440 --> 01:23:48.160
[Amit Varma]: One of course, is granting India dominions status and the other of course, was which

01:23:48.160 --> 01:23:52.720
[Amit Varma]: evolved in the second half of the decade was the appeasement of Hitler. But the interesting

01:23:52.720 --> 01:23:59.520
[Amit Varma]: point you were making there was that the conservatives almost got what they wanted, if not for Churchill,

01:23:59.520 --> 01:24:03.560
[Amit Varma]: and then we might still have been a dominion with the titular head being the British Queen

01:24:03.560 --> 01:24:08.560
[Amit Varma]: and as per you and as per conservatives, that's not a very bad state of affairs. So my question

01:24:08.560 --> 01:24:14.840
[Amit Varma]: to you, therefore, is a slightly mischievous question is that is independence, then a mistake

01:24:14.840 --> 01:24:20.840
[Amit Varma]: that we should regret, and it was accompanied by say, the horrors of partition, which you

01:24:20.840 --> 01:24:26.000
[Guest]: would expect with any radical act. So what would these are things that after the fact

01:24:26.000 --> 01:24:31.880
[Guest]: one can never really make judgments about counterfactuals, but let me first deal with

01:24:31.880 --> 01:24:38.960
[Guest]: the George the third thing. That's not my original idea. Leopold Emery, who was a minister

01:24:38.960 --> 01:24:43.280
[Guest]: in Churchill's cabinet, he has said, he was Secretary of State for India. He said Winston

01:24:43.280 --> 01:24:48.760
[Guest]: knows as much about India as George the third knew about the colony. So that's where the

01:24:48.760 --> 01:24:53.960
[Guest]: idea his own friend, colleague, schoolmate, he said that there's a history between Emery

01:24:53.960 --> 01:24:58.480
[Amit Varma]: and Churchill. Have you read Churchill's autobiography? My early days? No, I haven't. So in that there's

01:24:58.480 --> 01:25:03.400
[Amit Varma]: this funny incident where he goes to school, and he sees a small kid near the swimming

01:25:03.400 --> 01:25:08.600
[Amit Varma]: pool. And he goes and he pushes this kid in the swimming pool. And then that kid emerges

01:25:08.600 --> 01:25:13.160
[Amit Varma]: enraged and he chases Churchill around to beat him up. And it turns out that kid is

01:25:13.160 --> 01:25:18.520
[Amit Varma]: actually two years senior to him, and is Leopold Emery. And then Churchill calms him down by

01:25:18.520 --> 01:25:22.160
[Amit Varma]: saying that I'm sorry, I didn't know you were senior because you're so small. And then he

01:25:22.160 --> 01:25:25.840
[Amit Varma]: realizes that could be a faux pas. And he says, Okay, my father was also small, he was

01:25:25.840 --> 01:25:31.560
[Guest]: a great man. Anyway, that's a, that's a complete aside. They were good friends. But, but Emery

01:25:31.560 --> 01:25:36.800
[Guest]: was sensible. He said, Hey, this guy doesn't get it. Okay, now let's look at the counterfactuals

01:25:36.800 --> 01:25:43.200
[Guest]: that you've talked about. So Aminata Nair wrote a brilliant piece some years ago, about

01:25:43.200 --> 01:25:49.680
[Guest]: India becoming free in 47 and Hong Kong in 97. I mean, our British rule ending in Hong

01:25:49.680 --> 01:25:56.680
[Guest]: Kong. And he said, maybe Hong Kong lucked out by having 50 years of free markets and

01:25:56.680 --> 01:26:08.800
[Guest]: the stable British laws and, and free trade. So it's not obvious that independence is necessarily

01:26:08.800 --> 01:26:13.440
[Guest]: such a great thing. And in fact, Bernard Lewis has made this point when he talks about the

01:26:13.440 --> 01:26:19.640
[Guest]: Arab Middle East. He says independence is not the same as freedom. You can be a French

01:26:19.640 --> 01:26:23.920
[Guest]: colony Syria, then you become independent. Syrian people are no freer, they still have

01:26:23.920 --> 01:26:29.920
[Guest]: a dictator ruling them. So those are things that now there's also been a view has been

01:26:29.920 --> 01:26:37.800
[Guest]: a view when in the 30s, as this, especially after 1940, the Lahore resolution of the Muslim

01:26:37.800 --> 01:26:45.920
[Guest]: League, when this discussion kept going, there were two, three possibilities. One was to

01:26:45.920 --> 01:26:52.620
[Guest]: take someone like the Prince of Wales, and make him the titular head of a united India.

01:26:52.620 --> 01:27:00.920
[Guest]: So then this Hindu Muslim, the Muslim separatism for Pakistan automatically comes down. There

01:27:00.920 --> 01:27:09.160
[Guest]: was another move to go and find the last surviving descendant of Bahadur Shah Zafar and make

01:27:09.160 --> 01:27:15.400
[Guest]: him a titular emperor. So there were these kinds of ideas that were floated, it was not

01:27:15.400 --> 01:27:22.880
[Guest]: inconceivable that you could think of a dispensation which has a monarchical, because generally

01:27:22.880 --> 01:27:26.320
[Guest]: imperial dispensations tend to be monarchical.

01:27:26.320 --> 01:27:30.720
[Amit Varma]: In fact, at one point, Mahatma Gandhi made a throwaway comment that the Nizam of Hyderabad

01:27:30.720 --> 01:27:35.200
[Amit Varma]: could be the next emperor of India, to which Savarkar responded by saying that no, it should

01:27:35.200 --> 01:27:40.000
[Amit Varma]: be a Hindu kingdom with the king of Nepal on top, which is very amusing in hindsight.

01:27:40.000 --> 01:27:45.760
[Guest]: No, I think what if the Nizam had been made emperor, but it had been a constitutional

01:27:45.760 --> 01:27:50.960
[Guest]: monarchy, hey, it might have worked because it might have kept Pakistan. But you know,

01:27:50.960 --> 01:27:54.960
[Guest]: these are all counterfactuals. If you look in my book, I am now convinced that these

01:27:54.960 --> 01:28:01.640
[Guest]: are silly arguments that we should stop pursuing. Pakistan is a reality, it has happened. This

01:28:01.640 --> 01:28:06.240
[Guest]: idea of let's unite again, all together, all that is bogus, we should just move on.

01:28:06.240 --> 01:28:11.000
[Amit Varma]: But my question was not so much about the counterfactual, but about if you put yourself

01:28:11.000 --> 01:28:16.120
[Amit Varma]: back in that time, independence is clearly a radical idea, remaining part of the empire

01:28:16.120 --> 01:28:17.440
[Guest]: would be the conservative way to go.

01:28:17.440 --> 01:28:23.640
[Guest]: Everybody wanted that, Sapporo wanted that, Shastri wanted that. And finally, if you look

01:28:23.640 --> 01:28:30.360
[Guest]: at it for three years, we remained a dominion. In fact, that was V.P. Menon and Mountbatten's

01:28:30.360 --> 01:28:38.760
[Guest]: and Patel and Nehru's final decision to, and actually supported it. So, suppose we continued,

01:28:38.760 --> 01:28:42.960
[Guest]: kept a constitution, but remained a dominion, it's entirely possible we might be more like

01:28:42.960 --> 01:28:49.680
[Guest]: Canada or Australia today. I don't know. It's very difficult to, I think it might have been

01:28:49.680 --> 01:28:56.120
[Guest]: politically difficult. I think the movement under Mahatma, which was not a conservative

01:28:56.120 --> 01:29:00.240
[Guest]: movement, which was a radical movement, had radicalized the Indian masses a little too

01:29:00.240 --> 01:29:06.680
[Guest]: much. And I don't think people would have gone along with, they might have in 1935,

01:29:06.680 --> 01:29:07.680
[Amit Varma]: but not in 1947.

01:29:07.680 --> 01:29:13.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Speaking of sort of political difficulties, let's continue talking about the Raja Ram

01:29:13.080 --> 01:29:19.280
[Amit Varma]: Mohan Roy school, where, you know, we've gone through this early set of reformist conservatives

01:29:19.280 --> 01:29:24.640
[Amit Varma]: in your Navroji, Gokhale, Mehta, I presume you would ignore, and even Motilal Nehru to

01:29:24.640 --> 01:29:28.320
[Amit Varma]: an extent would probably fall within that.

01:29:28.320 --> 01:29:33.040
[Guest]: He was not a man of many ideas. So, there's no intellectual, there's not much intellectual

01:29:33.040 --> 01:29:35.320
[Guest]: stuff you can find as coming output out.

01:29:35.320 --> 01:29:40.000
[Amit Varma]: I think a lot of, from what little I know Motilal Nehru, it seems to me that he was

01:29:40.000 --> 01:29:45.040
[Amit Varma]: actually a classical liberal, who did believe in gradualism and working sort of.

01:29:45.040 --> 01:29:51.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's for sure. Let's move on to the, what you call the conservative caucus

01:29:51.800 --> 01:29:58.080
[Amit Varma]: within the Congress, where you point out that at the time India gained independent, we had

01:29:58.080 --> 01:30:02.120
[Amit Varma]: the three golden years where, I'll again quote from your book, quote, for the first three

01:30:02.120 --> 01:30:06.920
[Amit Varma]: years of independence till the new constitution came into force, the Ram Mohan Roy tradition

01:30:06.920 --> 01:30:11.840
[Amit Varma]: of conservatism held sway in the country. The erudite conservative Rajendra Prasad presided

01:30:11.840 --> 01:30:16.680
[Amit Varma]: over the Constituent Assembly. The incandescent conservative Raj Gopalachari succeeded Mount

01:30:16.680 --> 01:30:21.520
[Amit Varma]: Batten as a governor general. Ambedkar, a former member of the Vice Troy's council became

01:30:21.520 --> 01:30:25.440
[Amit Varma]: the chairman of the drafting committee for the constitution. Sardar Patel did defang

01:30:25.440 --> 01:30:29.520
[Amit Varma]: the princely order, not a very conservative thing to do, but he understood the value of

01:30:29.520 --> 01:30:35.360
[Amit Varma]: continuity if only symbolic. Stop quote. And I'll come back to, you know, you're claiming

01:30:35.360 --> 01:30:38.800
[Amit Varma]: Ambedkar as a conservative also after this.

01:30:38.800 --> 01:30:42.720
[Guest]: Ambedkar and Gandhi are, it's very difficult for anybody to claim them.

01:30:42.720 --> 01:30:44.200
[Guest]: They do contain multitudes.

01:30:44.200 --> 01:30:52.120
[Guest]: But the interesting thing is that many leftists call Gandhi a conservative. So, I find that

01:30:52.120 --> 01:30:59.200
[Guest]: tongue in cheek kind of funny and interesting. And Ambedkar, many people criticize him for

01:30:59.200 --> 01:31:03.240
[Guest]: having been in the Vice Troy's executive council as if that was a bad thing.

01:31:03.240 --> 01:31:04.240
[Unknown]: No, and your point was

01:31:04.240 --> 01:31:07.840
[Guest]: You know, he and the guy, what's his name, Bengali fellow, yeah, who was also in the

01:31:07.840 --> 01:31:12.120
[Guest]: Vice Troy's executive council, worked on Damodar Valley Corporation. They worked on

01:31:12.120 --> 01:31:19.480
[Guest]: constructive things. They were not stupid. You know, they're not unpatriotic at all.

01:31:19.480 --> 01:31:29.060
[Guest]: This binary, anybody who was pro-British Raj in any, even in a slight way, is not a patriot.

01:31:29.060 --> 01:31:34.920
[Guest]: Anybody who's gone to jail against a British Raj is a patriot is not acceptable.

01:31:34.920 --> 01:31:38.800
[Amit Varma]: I guess patriotism exists when the nation exists. But the point that you also made about

01:31:38.800 --> 01:31:44.680
[Amit Varma]: Ambedkar was that it was, in your view, a masterful move to make him in charge of drafting

01:31:44.680 --> 01:31:50.920
[Amit Varma]: the constitution because he brought conservatizing influence, if I can use that neologism, upon

01:31:50.920 --> 01:31:54.320
[Amit Varma]: the framing of the constitution. Explain that to me a little bit.

01:31:54.320 --> 01:32:01.800
[Guest]: See, the Government of India Act of 1935 has to be one of the finest pieces of legislation

01:32:01.800 --> 01:32:11.440
[Guest]: ever written up. It was drafted after extensive parliamentary discussions, committee discussions

01:32:11.440 --> 01:32:21.040
[Guest]: in Westminster. ATI was very actively involved in it. And it basically provided for pretty

01:32:21.040 --> 01:32:29.840
[Guest]: much the federal structure that we have today in India. It also provided for a relatively

01:32:29.840 --> 01:32:36.040
[Guest]: strong center, which is, again, what we have in India today. And offshoots after the Government

01:32:36.040 --> 01:32:39.880
[Guest]: of India Act came the Reserve Bank of India Act, this, that and the other. They were all

01:32:39.880 --> 01:32:46.640
[Guest]: came together as one bundle. They created the institutional framework for India going

01:32:46.640 --> 01:32:53.840
[Guest]: forward. We could have simply dropped that completely and gone after a French constitution

01:32:53.840 --> 01:33:00.240
[Guest]: or Austrian constitution or something, or even an American constitution. We chose not

01:33:00.240 --> 01:33:07.160
[Guest]: to. We chose to take the Government of India Act of 1935 and then add it, subtract it.

01:33:07.160 --> 01:33:13.840
[Guest]: And that's Ambedkar's principal contribution to the way the process worked, not the content,

01:33:13.840 --> 01:33:22.800
[Guest]: the process. For instance, first past the post. First past the post is very much there

01:33:22.800 --> 01:33:27.760
[Guest]: in Government of India Act, although remember at that time they had separate electorates.

01:33:27.760 --> 01:33:32.920
[Guest]: But within the electorates, it was first past the post within constituencies. Very English,

01:33:32.920 --> 01:33:38.040
[Guest]: very American. It's not there in continental constitutions, not there in the Israeli constitution.

01:33:38.040 --> 01:33:42.720
[Guest]: They're all about proportional representation. But this is what constituency based first

01:33:42.720 --> 01:33:47.720
[Guest]: past the post, which isn't what has given us stability and not the instability that

01:33:47.720 --> 01:33:58.680
[Guest]: France, Italy, and Israel constantly experience. These ideas were taken and taken forward how

01:33:58.680 --> 01:34:04.040
[Guest]: a comptroller and auditor general function. Very much there in 1935 Act. I mean, you know,

01:34:04.040 --> 01:34:11.160
[Guest]: the way the federal court was constituted or the Morris Quire. So, all of those paraphernalia

01:34:11.160 --> 01:34:20.000
[Guest]: were very well kept so that, in fact, on January 26, 1950, there was no discontinuity. And

01:34:20.000 --> 01:34:24.640
[Guest]: one of the interesting things that the Constitution of India did was all prevailing earlier laws

01:34:24.640 --> 01:34:29.160
[Guest]: will continue. Slowly we've changed them. You know, it took us a long time to change

01:34:29.160 --> 01:34:35.360
[Guest]: the one on homosexuality, but invariably we've been changing them over time. But it was not

01:34:35.360 --> 01:34:46.000
[Guest]: an abrupt thing. To my mind, that is the greatest achievement. Not jettisoning common law traditions,

01:34:46.000 --> 01:34:51.120
[Guest]: not jettisoning principles of equity traditions, not jettisoning the Government of India Act

01:34:51.120 --> 01:34:57.440
[Guest]: of 1935 completely, but building on it has ensured that our constitution sticks. I've

01:34:57.440 --> 01:35:01.680
[Guest]: lived in Latin America and in those countries every 10 years they change the constitution.

01:35:01.680 --> 01:35:06.840
[Guest]: There's complete instability and chaos as a result. You know, this has endured for more

01:35:06.840 --> 01:35:11.400
[Amit Varma]: than 70 years now. And, you know, I mean, it's been amended so often that people often

01:35:11.400 --> 01:35:16.000
[Amit Varma]: joke is a periodical and not a book. And, you know, you've kind of made the controversial

01:35:16.000 --> 01:35:20.480
[Amit Varma]: point in your book that it's a conservative constitution, whereas a lot of other people

01:35:20.480 --> 01:35:24.840
[Amit Varma]: would view it as a fairly radical constitution. You know, Gautam Bhatia had a recent book

01:35:24.840 --> 01:35:29.920
[Amit Varma]: out with the title Transformative Constitution, which sort of sums it up. And I did an episode

01:35:29.920 --> 01:35:34.200
[Amit Varma]: with the political scientist Rahul Verma, who's written a book with Pradeep Chabbar

01:35:34.200 --> 01:35:42.760
[Amit Varma]: called Identity and Ideology. And his point there was that this was a radical constitution

01:35:42.760 --> 01:35:47.800
[Amit Varma]: and that conservatives were up in arms. I mean, he didn't call them conservatisms, but

01:35:47.800 --> 01:35:53.600
[Amit Varma]: the fault line here, the ideological fault line was one of statism, where conservatives

01:35:53.600 --> 01:35:58.120
[Amit Varma]: and I don't think he used that term because he avoided those terms in that book, but I'm

01:35:58.120 --> 01:36:03.520
[Amit Varma]: using it, but that conservatives felt that society is fine as it is, and the state should

01:36:03.520 --> 01:36:10.040
[Amit Varma]: not try to do social engineering and reshape it. And the liberals or the radicals who shaped

01:36:10.040 --> 01:36:13.880
[Amit Varma]: the constitution felt that no, society does need to be reshaped.

01:36:13.880 --> 01:36:21.960
[Guest]: Yeah, the issue really, if you think about it, despite all their pretensions to whatever

01:36:21.960 --> 01:36:28.760
[Guest]: the British never abolished untouchability, for instance, technically untouchability existed

01:36:28.760 --> 01:36:35.240
[Guest]: in British India. Having said that, the most egregious forms of untouchability actually

01:36:35.240 --> 01:36:40.600
[Guest]: existed in the native states, in Travancore, for instance, not in British India. And in

01:36:40.600 --> 01:36:47.520
[Guest]: British India, Ambedkar or Rabadu Srinivasan or anyone got education, got, they were able

01:36:47.520 --> 01:36:57.800
[Guest]: to make their impact. And they had votes. Voting was given by property and education,

01:36:57.800 --> 01:37:06.160
[Guest]: not by caste. So the Government of India Act of 1935 gave as many Dalits who were educated

01:37:06.160 --> 01:37:11.920
[Guest]: and who had property and paid taxes, they gave them the vote, it was not based on caste.

01:37:11.920 --> 01:37:17.600
[Guest]: So it is true that abolition of untouchability was a radical act or seen as a radical act

01:37:17.600 --> 01:37:24.760
[Guest]: by many people. But I see it as part of the evolutionary process. I see it as going back

01:37:24.760 --> 01:37:29.200
[Guest]: to Macaulay, going back to Nankumar being hanged under war in his things. He was a Brahmin

01:37:29.200 --> 01:37:33.760
[Guest]: and he was hanged. And there was a big furor in Calcutta, not so much whether he was guilty

01:37:33.760 --> 01:37:40.240
[Guest]: or not guilty, but whether it was okay to hang a Brahmin. So each step it has moved

01:37:40.240 --> 01:37:49.880
[Guest]: on. And so I see many of the so-called radical changes done in 1950 as being built on the

01:37:49.880 --> 01:37:57.520
[Guest]: changes of 1909, of 1919, of 1935. And the continuous evolution, going back all the way

01:37:57.520 --> 01:38:02.440
[Guest]: to the Regulating Act and British India Act in the late 18th century, from then till now.

01:38:02.440 --> 01:38:07.040
[Guest]: Queen's Proclamation of 1858, it talks about no discrimination based on caste, creed or

01:38:07.040 --> 01:38:11.840
[Guest]: religion. British didn't always follow it. I'm not saying they followed it, but principle

01:38:11.840 --> 01:38:17.840
[Guest]: is enunciated and there is this gradual evolution. So I disagree with both the people you've

01:38:17.840 --> 01:38:23.560
[Guest]: interviewed from the perspective of historical process. I'm not talking about every detail

01:38:23.560 --> 01:38:28.600
[Guest]: of content. There are changes in content in the Constitution, which are quite radical.

01:38:28.600 --> 01:38:35.360
[Guest]: But the processes, the radical step is a next step from a step taken 10 years earlier. That's

01:38:35.360 --> 01:38:40.520
[Guest]: the way I see it. We had limited franchise. Now we had adult franchise. But at no stage,

01:38:40.520 --> 01:38:49.320
[Guest]: by the way, was franchise based on gender or caste. Never. It was based on property,

01:38:49.320 --> 01:38:54.120
[Guest]: on tax payment and education. So that was eliminated and just age was made. Anybody

01:38:54.120 --> 01:39:01.320
[Guest]: over 21 can vote. And so I see that as a step rather than as a radical break. So it's the

01:39:01.320 --> 01:39:06.800
[Guest]: way you want to look at the history of the evolution of the Constitution and just look

01:39:06.800 --> 01:39:16.240
[Guest]: at our neighbor, two of our neighbors. Pakistan never kind of built on the Government of India

01:39:16.240 --> 01:39:20.520
[Guest]: Act of 1935. Instead, Ayub Khan came up with something called basic democracy, which was

01:39:20.520 --> 01:39:25.360
[Guest]: a completely new idea. I'm not saying it's a good idea, a bad idea, but it was a radical

01:39:25.360 --> 01:39:29.360
[Guest]: and that never worked. It worked for five years and then that went and another constitution

01:39:29.360 --> 01:39:35.520
[Guest]: came. Sri Lanka, they're troubling themselves going back and forth between this and that

01:39:35.520 --> 01:39:42.720
[Guest]: Prime Minister presidential and never resolving this. And in fact, creating it doesn't mean

01:39:42.720 --> 01:39:48.280
[Guest]: we don't amend. Of course, we amend, but we still keep that continuity as we amend. And

01:39:48.280 --> 01:39:54.440
[Guest]: that is the principal desiderata of conservatism.

01:39:54.440 --> 01:40:02.280
[Amit Varma]: Let's let's kind of go back to the chronology and sort of the Ram Mohan Roy conservatives,

01:40:02.280 --> 01:40:06.840
[Amit Varma]: as you say, and for three years during the transitional period, 47 to 50, they are in

01:40:06.840 --> 01:40:11.280
[Amit Varma]: powerful positions, they are shaping the new India. And then in a sense for that, for that

01:40:11.280 --> 01:40:16.040
[Amit Varma]: strand of conservatism, it all falls apart. Patel dies, Prasad gets a titular post of

01:40:16.040 --> 01:40:21.360
[Amit Varma]: President, Purushottam Das Tandon is knocked out of the party, Govind Ballapant is CM of

01:40:21.360 --> 01:40:27.840
[Amit Varma]: UP, but he's kind of sidelined as well. And, and it's all Nehru, VP Menon, they're sort

01:40:27.840 --> 01:40:30.080
[Amit Varma]: of Fabian socialist vision, which is dominating.

01:40:30.080 --> 01:40:31.080
[Amit Varma]: VK Menon, not VP.

01:40:31.080 --> 01:40:32.080
[Amit Varma]: Sorry, yeah.

01:40:32.080 --> 01:40:33.080
[Guest]: VP Menon's a good guy.

01:40:33.080 --> 01:40:37.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah. Sorry, my bad. VP Menon helped bring all the states together, of course,

01:40:37.960 --> 01:40:44.560
[Amit Varma]: and has written a fine book on it. And, you know, and like you point out, there were some

01:40:44.560 --> 01:40:50.560
[Amit Varma]: minor successes, such as they did manage to stop Nehru from carrying out collective farming.

01:40:50.560 --> 01:40:57.080
[Guest]: 20 million people died in China. We don't know how many people died under Stalin in

01:40:57.080 --> 01:41:05.240
[Guest]: in Russia, because they didn't keep track of killings. Collective farming could have

01:41:05.240 --> 01:41:12.040
[Guest]: set back Indian agriculture, could have, could have created massive chaos. And there was

01:41:12.040 --> 01:41:20.880
[Guest]: a very strong lobby for it. So, Tantra Party fought it relentlessly. Charan Singh, who

01:41:20.880 --> 01:41:23.880
[Guest]: was in and out of the Congress Party, actually, at that time, I think he was in the Congress

01:41:23.880 --> 01:41:33.400
[Guest]: Party, fought it relentlessly. And somehow, the caucus prevailed. And Nehru's other advisors

01:41:33.400 --> 01:41:39.980
[Guest]: who wanted to push us towards collective farming were kept back. Also, remember, at that time,

01:41:39.980 --> 01:41:44.200
[Guest]: property was a fundamental right. This obscene amendment hadn't yet come.

01:41:44.200 --> 01:41:48.760
[Amit Varma]: I had an episode on the right to property. And I agree with you, that is the most obscene

01:41:48.760 --> 01:41:49.760
[Guest]: amendment.

01:41:49.760 --> 01:41:53.840
[Guest]: This obscene amendment hadn't yet come. And Nehru never, Nehru disliked property being

01:41:53.840 --> 01:42:01.240
[Guest]: a fundamental right. He disliked the idea of justiciable compensation. But he was gradualist

01:42:01.240 --> 01:42:08.560
[Guest]: enough not to tamper with it. It happened after his death. So, yes, we started, I think

01:42:08.560 --> 01:42:18.600
[Guest]: the high point of losing influence was 56, 55, Avadi Congress, after which it became

01:42:18.600 --> 01:42:27.640
[Guest]: very much of a left-wing, pro-Soviet, pro-central planning, pro-gigantism party on the economic

01:42:27.640 --> 01:42:38.260
[Guest]: side. And on the political side, I think it remained one of kind of tops-down fixes. Community

01:42:38.260 --> 01:42:44.680
[Guest]: development program, he will spend 500 crores, you know, some tops-down stuff without sufficient

01:42:44.680 --> 01:42:52.040
[Guest]: citizen participation or grassroots involvements. And making some compromises like linguistic

01:42:52.040 --> 01:42:58.360
[Guest]: states, which they couldn't fight off completely. And it was a very sad time for the country,

01:42:58.360 --> 01:43:01.800
[Guest]: very sad time. And it continued for a long time, unfortunately.

01:43:01.800 --> 01:43:06.920
[Amit Varma]: No, and it was in an economic sense, I admire Nehru for many things. And I think he was

01:43:06.920 --> 01:43:11.360
[Amit Varma]: a great statesman, but in economics, he was a complete disaster. And this would definitely

01:43:11.360 --> 01:43:15.400
[Amit Varma]: have been part of the reason that there weren't enough countervailing influences and he sidelined

01:43:15.400 --> 01:43:17.240
[Guest]: Raj Gopalachari and forced him to leave.

01:43:17.240 --> 01:43:22.680
[Guest]: I actually hold as economic advisors more responsible than even Nehru, Malo Nubesvi,

01:43:22.680 --> 01:43:32.680
[Guest]: K. R. V. Rao, K. N. Raj, all these, Sukumoy Chakravarti, all these fellows who kept writing

01:43:32.680 --> 01:43:40.680
[Guest]: theoretical papers sitting in Delhi school, and who really sidelined the chinoys of the

01:43:40.680 --> 01:43:48.680
[Guest]: world and pushed through some very absurd, I mean, Malo Nubesvi actually believed that

01:43:48.680 --> 01:43:55.080
[Guest]: the economy was some kind of a machine. He had no time for price signals, for, you know,

01:43:55.080 --> 01:43:58.960
[Guest]: consumer preferences. Everything was a machine and it would work. If you made so much steel,

01:43:58.960 --> 01:44:03.280
[Guest]: you could make so many cars. If you made so many cars, you could consume so much petrol.

01:44:03.280 --> 01:44:06.840
[Amit Varma]: And it's ironic because Hayek's great essay, The Use of Knowledge in Society, was written

01:44:06.840 --> 01:44:07.840
[Guest]: in I think, 45 or 46 before.

01:44:07.840 --> 01:44:15.240
[Guest]: All this was known, Baba. There's no, the idea that they didn't know that this was zeitgeist.

01:44:15.240 --> 01:44:19.760
[Guest]: I know people like Ram Goha pushed this idea. No, no, they were just, you know, following

01:44:19.760 --> 01:44:21.080
[Guest]: the fashions of that time.

01:44:21.080 --> 01:44:25.280
[Amit Varma]: Which I think broadly is true. I mean, no one knew what the Soviet Union actually was

01:44:25.280 --> 01:44:26.640
[Guest]: at that time. People sort of idealized it.

01:44:26.640 --> 01:44:32.520
[Guest]: They had put the Sputnik in space. So people thought they were ahead of the US and the

01:44:32.520 --> 01:44:41.280
[Guest]: West. So there was that kind of, but there was also, I think, brazen stupidity for which

01:44:41.280 --> 01:44:45.200
[Guest]: we are all paying a price. I mean, the point is, it's not a price that they only paid or

01:44:45.200 --> 01:44:48.440
[Guest]: their families paid. It's a price that the whole country has paid.

01:44:48.440 --> 01:44:52.040
[Amit Varma]: I want to move on to the Bankimchandra Chatterjee School because it's sort of more relevant

01:44:52.040 --> 01:44:56.640
[Amit Varma]: to our times. But before I do that, let's talk about the last political gasp of the

01:44:56.640 --> 01:45:00.600
[Amit Varma]: Ram Mohan Roy School. And of course, you have the Conservative Caucus sort of dying out

01:45:00.600 --> 01:45:05.680
[Amit Varma]: within the Congress when, you know, Shastri dies, Gulzarilal Nanda leaves, Maraji Desai

01:45:05.680 --> 01:45:10.480
[Amit Varma]: leaves. And by the end of that decade, by the end of the 60s, Svatantra Party is also

01:45:10.480 --> 01:45:18.080
[Amit Varma]: a spent force. And your point is that politically, the Svatantra Party and by extension, the

01:45:18.080 --> 01:45:23.800
[Amit Varma]: Ram Mohan Roy School of Conservatism is doomed to fail politically. Why do you say that?

01:45:23.800 --> 01:45:32.080
[Guest]: As a separate political movement, institution or party, I don't think it can succeed. In

01:45:32.080 --> 01:45:42.040
[Guest]: democratic politics, the issue that seems to matter most to voters is identity. And

01:45:42.040 --> 01:45:48.800
[Guest]: if at all there is an interest in economics, the interest seems to be in redistributive,

01:45:48.800 --> 01:45:55.080
[Guest]: goody giving, patronage economics. So, this is the nature of the voter. And this has been

01:45:55.080 --> 01:46:01.720
[Guest]: discussed even by Pericles. I mean, this is not a new thing. The nature of the voter is

01:46:01.720 --> 01:46:06.160
[Guest]: something we have to live with, which is one reason, by the way, why many aristocracies

01:46:06.160 --> 01:46:12.200
[Guest]: resisted increasing the franchise. I'm not supporting it, but I'm saying there was always

01:46:12.200 --> 01:46:18.880
[Guest]: this fear that now, if you're going to vote by identity, like the Republican Party in

01:46:18.880 --> 01:46:25.280
[Guest]: America is about guns, it is about abortion, it's about immigration. It's not about taxes

01:46:25.280 --> 01:46:32.200
[Guest]: and trade. Those are secondary issues. The Conservative Party in England is about England

01:46:32.200 --> 01:46:39.040
[Guest]: and identity and so on. And the Labour is about free immigration and more refugees and

01:46:39.040 --> 01:46:44.240
[Guest]: so on. These are about identity issues. It's not about... And then the ideology, the economic

01:46:44.240 --> 01:46:49.280
[Guest]: ideology comes. Now, what is the identity issue that Swatantra or Ram Mohan Liberal

01:46:49.280 --> 01:46:57.400
[Guest]: can put up? Very difficult. It's too elitist. You don't appeal to any one caste or any religion

01:46:57.400 --> 01:47:03.600
[Guest]: or any linguistic group. You can't call yourself Telugu Desam. You can't call yourself, you

01:47:03.600 --> 01:47:13.520
[Guest]: know, Muslim League or Kalidhal. So, therefore, to get elected is not possible. That's my

01:47:13.520 --> 01:47:20.160
[Guest]: point I'm trying to make. A party like this as a political party. Now, can it be a movement?

01:47:20.160 --> 01:47:25.240
[Guest]: Can it be a debating society? After all, Fabian Society, that left-wing group that did so

01:47:25.240 --> 01:47:31.400
[Guest]: much damage to the 20th century, it was just a debating group. So, you can influence without

01:47:31.400 --> 01:47:37.960
[Guest]: necessarily being a political party. That's the point I'm trying to make. And to try and

01:47:37.960 --> 01:47:40.900
[Guest]: start a political party is a waste of time.

01:47:40.900 --> 01:47:47.000
[Amit Varma]: No, the Ram Mohan School of Conservatism sort of failed there, at least in a political sense.

01:47:47.000 --> 01:47:51.320
[Amit Varma]: But the strand of conservatism which did succeed was the Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay strand

01:47:51.320 --> 01:47:55.320
[Guest]: of conservatism, which no one expected. And they're in charge now.

01:47:55.320 --> 01:48:03.680
[Guest]: Particularly in the 50s, I don't think Jansang had more than 3, 4, 5 MPs, whatever. The communists

01:48:03.680 --> 01:48:12.040
[Guest]: always had many more. No one expected the Bankim Chandra School to do so well politically.

01:48:12.040 --> 01:48:20.680
[Guest]: And that's in the 62 and 67 elections. Swatantra had more seats than Jansang. So, but the reason

01:48:20.680 --> 01:48:28.560
[Guest]: I think that's been able to chug along and increase its footprint, frankly, goes back

01:48:28.560 --> 01:48:38.040
[Guest]: to Lajpat Rai. It goes back to, and even to Bandarkar. Bandarkar's speech talks about

01:48:38.040 --> 01:48:49.040
[Guest]: the fact that, hey, you know, Hindus better become anti-caste. We better get consolidation

01:48:49.040 --> 01:48:53.000
[Guest]: across castes. And this is also very prominent in Savarkar's writings.

01:48:53.000 --> 01:48:54.000
[Amit Varma]: So,

01:48:54.000 --> 01:48:58.680
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Savarkar and Ambedkar were together against Gandhi on the issue of caste. A lot

01:48:58.680 --> 01:49:00.480
[Amit Varma]: of people don't realize this when they sort of

01:49:00.480 --> 01:49:06.600
[Guest]: Yeah, so there's, and that in the initial years, when I was in college, for instance,

01:49:06.600 --> 01:49:16.000
[Guest]: in the 60s, Jansang was a North Indian Hindu, Hindi party. And that too upper caste, you

01:49:16.000 --> 01:49:23.480
[Guest]: know, light complexioned people, kind of party. It has changed. Its current leader is an OBC.

01:49:23.480 --> 01:49:30.080
[Guest]: I mean, hey, it's, it's been able to do what, in fact, Kanshi Ram always used to say a communist

01:49:30.080 --> 01:49:36.000
[Guest]: party of India is a joke. All its politburo are Brahmins and upper caste. All the workers

01:49:36.000 --> 01:49:42.200
[Guest]: are Dalits. And that has been the problem with virtually all political parties in India.

01:49:42.200 --> 01:49:48.320
[Guest]: They have been able to break that genuine Hindu consolidation that Lajpat Rai politically

01:49:48.320 --> 01:49:55.840
[Guest]: wanted and which Bhandarkar intellectually argued for and Savarkar supported in his early

01:49:55.840 --> 01:50:02.280
[Guest]: days. That has happened. It's happened for a variety of reasons, including I mentioned

01:50:02.280 --> 01:50:08.200
[Guest]: somewhere in the book, the Ramayan television series of what is this fellow, this

01:50:08.200 --> 01:50:09.200
[Guest]: Ramanand Sagar

01:50:09.200 --> 01:50:16.080
[Guest]: In cultural history terms, he'll go down as important as Kambanur Tulsi, Das or Tyagaraja.

01:50:16.080 --> 01:50:21.160
[Guest]: Just wait and see when it's written a hundred years from now, the importance of what he

01:50:21.160 --> 01:50:26.800
[Guest]: did. But for a variety of reasons, they have been able to, but I think this is the single

01:50:26.800 --> 01:50:35.800
[Guest]: most important reason. The identity of a Samajwadi party is as of a Yadav party. The identity

01:50:35.800 --> 01:50:43.240
[Guest]: of NCPs as of a Maratha party, for Kalidhar as a Jat Seekh party. This has managed to

01:50:43.240 --> 01:50:53.760
[Guest]: take the identity across castes and has been able to get OBCs into it. This was very much

01:50:53.760 --> 01:51:01.080
[Guest]: Lajpat Rai's vision and that has happened. It's almost as if they've kind of systematically,

01:51:01.080 --> 01:51:11.160
[Guest]: they've also looked at the ideas going back to Bankim. What is the original idea of Anandamath?

01:51:11.160 --> 01:51:19.360
[Guest]: A dedicated group of Sanyasis, Bhairagis, who are worshippers of the mother goddess,

01:51:19.360 --> 01:51:29.960
[Guest]: who are committed to sacrifice and freedom. Actually, today's BJP vocabulary is uncannily

01:51:29.960 --> 01:51:42.880
[Guest]: similar. Vande Mataram, Mother India, spirit of sacrifice, spirit of asceticism, anti-corruption.

01:51:42.880 --> 01:51:50.080
[Guest]: On the ideas side, they have gone back to Bankim quite well. On the organizational and

01:51:50.080 --> 01:51:56.680
[Guest]: people side, they have been the most successful party in terms of they have a Dalit president.

01:51:56.680 --> 01:52:01.160
[Guest]: Before that, they even made Muslim president. So, they've kind of been able to do these

01:52:01.160 --> 01:52:10.280
[Guest]: things quite well. And really, I'm quite impressed. The adherence to Bankim and the ongoing Vivekananda.

01:52:10.280 --> 01:52:18.200
[Guest]: Vivekananda is very important in Modi's vocabulary. And again, the same ideas of sacrifice of

01:52:18.200 --> 01:52:25.840
[Guest]: motherland, those ideas taken forward and mingled with the political organization of

01:52:25.840 --> 01:52:31.840
[Guest]: how in a democratic polity does one get the OBC vote? How does one get the Dalit vote?

01:52:31.840 --> 01:52:36.440
[Guest]: How does one get the tribal vote? And long years of hard work, particularly the tribal

01:52:36.440 --> 01:52:45.240
[Guest]: votes is not recent. I mean, that work has been going on for 30-40 years in parts of

01:52:45.240 --> 01:52:52.480
[Guest]: tribal India, and it's finally paid off. So, there's still a problem with the South. It's

01:52:52.480 --> 01:53:00.040
[Guest]: not clear that it's been able to. Karnataka is a bit of a, you know, one swallow not making

01:53:00.040 --> 01:53:06.080
[Guest]: a summer. So, we'll see if they'll be able to push through in Telangana, Andhra, Kerala,

01:53:06.080 --> 01:53:12.880
[Guest]: Tamil Nadu. But the overall effect has been very, very interesting. Also, the base of

01:53:12.880 --> 01:53:19.080
[Guest]: the leadership, the original Hindu Mahasabha leadership was really very much Bengali and

01:53:19.080 --> 01:53:28.840
[Guest]: Punjabi and UP maybe. And the original RSS leadership was, you know, Maharashtra Vidarbha.

01:53:28.840 --> 01:53:34.000
[Guest]: Now you have Gujarat, you have, you know, different parts of the country pushing forth

01:53:34.000 --> 01:53:38.380
[Amit Varma]: the leaders. You have an OBC Prime Minister. I'll sort of synthesize all this by quoting

01:53:38.380 --> 01:53:43.080
[Amit Varma]: from your book again, which very eloquently expresses sort of the origin of the school

01:53:43.080 --> 01:53:48.000
[Amit Varma]: of where you say, quote, a frequently asked question is whether Hindu nationalism by its

01:53:48.000 --> 01:53:53.200
[Amit Varma]: very Hindu and very nationalistic nature can be a branch of conservatism at all. This needs

01:53:53.200 --> 01:53:57.880
[Amit Varma]: to be viewed contextually. Abraham Lincoln, who was perhaps the greatest American president,

01:53:57.880 --> 01:54:03.080
[Amit Varma]: referred to the mystic chords of memory that bind people together. When you combine this

01:54:03.080 --> 01:54:07.160
[Amit Varma]: with the fact that the British conquered India and pretty openly took the position that they

01:54:07.160 --> 01:54:12.160
[Amit Varma]: had conquered it from predominantly Muslim rulers, it became clear that non-Muslims in

01:54:12.160 --> 01:54:17.760
[Amit Varma]: India, taking into account that the very term Hindu was an evolving one, had no option but

01:54:17.760 --> 01:54:23.120
[Amit Varma]: to seek a renaissance if they were to sustain themselves as a community with shared mutual

01:54:23.120 --> 01:54:28.880
[Amit Varma]: loyalty rather than as atomized splinters. Bankim and Lajpat Rai, along with several

01:54:28.880 --> 01:54:34.480
[Amit Varma]: others realized that a shared Hindu cultural identity could be the basis of overcoming

01:54:34.480 --> 01:54:41.040
[Amit Varma]: vertical and horizontal boundaries among Hindus like caste, stop quote. And you later said

01:54:41.040 --> 01:54:45.720
[Amit Varma]: they could then be a band of brothers. And partly, like you said, this has finally taken

01:54:45.720 --> 01:54:50.200
[Amit Varma]: shape in the sense that more Dalits voted for the BJP than the Congress in both the

01:54:50.200 --> 01:54:56.080
[Guest]: 2014 and the 2019 elections. In UP, there might be as many Dalits voting for BJP as

01:54:56.080 --> 01:55:02.440
[Amit Varma]: for BSP. Absolutely. So, you know, it's quite an achievement. Whatever, whatever activists

01:55:02.440 --> 01:55:07.160
[Amit Varma]: on the outside might say, it seems the Dalits of India have voted with their feet for the

01:55:07.160 --> 01:55:13.160
[Amit Varma]: moment. Now, I want to come back to a slightly more sort of troubling element. There's a

01:55:13.160 --> 01:55:18.040
[Amit Varma]: later quote in your book, the question that arises a quote, the question that arises is

01:55:18.040 --> 01:55:22.720
[Amit Varma]: whether the pre-independence Hindu nationalist movement was a conservative one or not. It

01:55:22.720 --> 01:55:28.520
[Amit Varma]: certainly had a conservative flavor to it. But it also had a revivalist and rejectionist

01:55:28.520 --> 01:55:35.000
[Amit Varma]: flavor, stop quote. And in a different part of the book, you talk about how the danger

01:55:35.000 --> 01:55:41.960
[Amit Varma]: in these kinds of nationalistic movements can be in othering certain people the same

01:55:41.960 --> 01:55:46.360
[Amit Varma]: way the Nazis did, for example, and you bring up that comparison, and you say that that

01:55:46.360 --> 01:55:51.280
[Amit Varma]: othering could become something pathological, and could descend into something which is

01:55:51.280 --> 01:55:54.440
[Amit Varma]: very far from conservatism. Can you sort of elaborate?

01:55:54.440 --> 01:56:04.400
[Guest]: Yeah, you see, when you talk about revivalist, if you say that only Gupta era or Chola era

01:56:04.400 --> 01:56:13.240
[Guest]: stuff matters, the last 200 years of British era is all hell, is all poison, all to be

01:56:13.240 --> 01:56:20.560
[Guest]: forgotten, all to be jettisoned, that is revivalism. You know, that is not conservatism. The second

01:56:20.560 --> 01:56:26.960
[Guest]: thing in terms of othering is really, Band of Brothers is, we are together, we have a

01:56:26.960 --> 01:56:33.680
[Guest]: shared culture, we have a shared community, a shared territory, whatever. Does it require

01:56:33.680 --> 01:56:41.200
[Guest]: that we move to the next step of disliking another Band of Brothers? And so that's called

01:56:41.200 --> 01:56:48.800
[Guest]: othering, really, essentially, to build a kind of political platform on a negative kind

01:56:48.800 --> 01:56:55.960
[Guest]: of trajectory. And it's not unusual, it happens. You could be a proud German, and you could

01:56:55.960 --> 01:57:02.640
[Guest]: have included the Jews as part of proud Germans. After all, between 1900 and 1930, although

01:57:02.640 --> 01:57:08.040
[Guest]: they were 1% of the population, 30% of the Nobel prizes won by Germans were won by Jewish

01:57:08.040 --> 01:57:14.960
[Guest]: Germans. They never thought of themselves. But if you choose to other them, then you

01:57:14.960 --> 01:57:21.120
[Guest]: end up with a pathological situation, which in the long run can be detrimental, can come

01:57:21.120 --> 01:57:27.400
[Guest]: back like a Basmasurah, it can come back to actually kill you. And this is a problem that

01:57:27.400 --> 01:57:37.960
[Guest]: a lot of nationalist conservative movements have. Parnell was, you know, look at Parnell,

01:57:37.960 --> 01:57:44.040
[Guest]: how he was othered. He was a great Irish Catholic leader. But the church went against him because

01:57:44.040 --> 01:57:50.240
[Guest]: he had an affair or something. Purely personal reason, you othered the man. And then the

01:57:50.240 --> 01:57:56.120
[Guest]: Irish lost 50 years, that they could have gotten their home rule earlier, under Parnell.

01:57:56.120 --> 01:58:01.720
[Guest]: So these things, you have to be very careful, you have to be extremely careful that you

01:58:01.720 --> 01:58:09.440
[Guest]: don't. And that's why revivalism and being anti-British, and anti-McCauley-Putra, and

01:58:09.440 --> 01:58:16.360
[Guest]: anti-British rule, and anti-English, ends up also becoming anti-Western civilization,

01:58:16.360 --> 01:58:21.240
[Guest]: which is the source of so much modern good stuff for us. So it's dangerous. You should

01:58:21.240 --> 01:58:27.240
[Guest]: not other, you know, anyone because in doing that, you lose. I mean, TSA Ledder is not

01:58:27.240 --> 01:58:31.880
[Guest]: a fool to read the Upanishad. He's, you know, he's reaching out to all that is great in

01:58:31.880 --> 01:58:38.360
[Guest]: human traditions. We should be like that and not other, either the West or Muslims or anyone.

01:58:38.360 --> 01:58:42.480
[Amit Varma]: And there's a passage in your book, which seemed to me that I would have agreed with

01:58:42.480 --> 01:58:47.080
[Amit Varma]: if you had written it in, say, 2002, when Vajpayee was Prime Minister. But I cannot

01:58:47.080 --> 01:58:52.240
[Amit Varma]: agree with it today, which is, quote, almost imperceptibly, the face of Hindu nationalism

01:58:52.240 --> 01:58:57.320
[Amit Varma]: changed. Gone was the opposition to English and the attempts to force Hindi and reluctant

01:58:57.320 --> 01:59:02.240
[Amit Varma]: states. Traces of obscurantism associated with the revivalist ideology were quietly

01:59:02.240 --> 01:59:06.760
[Amit Varma]: jettisoned. The Ram Rajya Parishad's opposition to changes to the Hindu marriage and divorce

01:59:06.760 --> 01:59:12.440
[Amit Varma]: code would appear quaint today. Hindu nationalism has acquired a chic contemporary age. Stop

01:59:12.440 --> 01:59:17.480
[Amit Varma]: quote. And even if this might have been true in 2002, when Vajpayee was PM, it seems to

01:59:17.480 --> 01:59:22.120
[Amit Varma]: me that it's actually shifted the other way today in the sense that cow is back as an

01:59:22.120 --> 01:59:27.480
[Amit Varma]: issue. Now that they're done with 370, they're at some point going to move on to the uniform

01:59:27.480 --> 01:59:32.800
[Amit Varma]: civil code, which in a sense is, you know, the Hindu code bill issue all over again,

01:59:32.800 --> 01:59:37.600
[Amit Varma]: expressed differently as resentment against the other, you know, apply to everyone. Similarly,

01:59:37.600 --> 01:59:41.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, lynchings are on the rise. You have talk of, you know, I mean, things like love

01:59:41.760 --> 01:59:47.280
[Amit Varma]: jihad and all were issues in the 1920s, for God's sake, and they are back. I had an episode

01:59:47.280 --> 01:59:51.880
[Amit Varma]: a while back with Akar Patel on the intellectual foundations of Hindutva, which in retrospect,

01:59:51.880 --> 01:59:55.880
[Amit Varma]: I think both of us said things which were rather naive. But one of the points he made

01:59:55.880 --> 02:00:03.600
[Amit Varma]: in that was that it seems to him that a lot of Hindutva, it seems to be again, like you

02:00:03.600 --> 02:00:09.400
[Amit Varma]: pointed out about the other, it's directed at someone, you know, whether it's cow slaughter

02:00:09.400 --> 02:00:14.640
[Amit Varma]: directed at Muslims, whether it's UCC directed at Muslims or at appeasement of the Muslims

02:00:14.640 --> 02:00:19.880
[Amit Varma]: that the Congress carried out. And that allegation, of course, is correct. But it's all about

02:00:19.880 --> 02:00:26.840
[Guest]: the other. What are the positive things that this I think, I think, you know, the the best

02:00:26.840 --> 02:00:33.760
[Guest]: writings of Savarkar or Shamprasad. It's not about the other at all. It's about reforming

02:00:33.760 --> 02:00:39.000
[Guest]: and consolidating Hindus. It's very little reference to the other actually. Hindutva

02:00:39.000 --> 02:00:45.840
[Amit Varma]: has a fair amount of reference to it. I mean, I've read it and but the emphasis is really

02:00:45.840 --> 02:00:54.440
[Guest]: let's fix ourselves. Let Hindus get, you know, Sangatan within Hindus that let's let's get

02:00:54.440 --> 02:01:00.000
[Guest]: rid of caste. Let's get rid of egregious. That's the emphasis. The other part is kind

02:01:00.000 --> 02:01:08.320
[Guest]: of there, but it's not and it can always become bigger. The question is, if it becomes bigger,

02:01:08.320 --> 02:01:14.200
[Guest]: what are the risks? What are the dangers? There's two others. There's not I don't believe

02:01:14.200 --> 02:01:19.880
[Guest]: there's only one other. One other is the West. Because when you reject English and Macaulay

02:01:19.880 --> 02:01:26.360
[Guest]: Putras, and when you reject a lot of those things, you are saying that we will be a kind

02:01:26.360 --> 02:01:34.200
[Guest]: of a Hindu thing without recourse to any interaction dependence with the West. And the other is

02:01:34.200 --> 02:01:43.040
[Guest]: Muslim. I think the second one, post 911, has gotten a little confused with also this

02:01:43.040 --> 02:01:48.320
[Guest]: jihadism and international terrorism, and of course, Pakistan sponsored terrorism and

02:01:48.320 --> 02:01:56.380
[Guest]: so on. So that's become a very confused area of of dealing with it. And I don't think anybody

02:01:56.380 --> 02:02:03.040
[Guest]: has the right answers. I just saw the other day that there is a head of some Christian

02:02:03.040 --> 02:02:09.200
[Guest]: association in Kerala was written a long letter about love jihad saying, it's all about Christian

02:02:09.200 --> 02:02:15.160
[Guest]: girls who are being trapped in love jihad. So this is now, you know, and the attack on

02:02:15.160 --> 02:02:20.360
[Guest]: the Christian churches in Sri Lanka and so on. This has become a bit of a difficult thing

02:02:20.360 --> 02:02:27.680
[Guest]: to deal with. One can only hope and I've mentioned that there are some good signs. There are

02:02:27.680 --> 02:02:35.360
[Guest]: some lots of worrisome signs, some good signs. Modi being the chief guest at the International

02:02:35.360 --> 02:02:44.920
[Guest]: Sufi Convention in Delhi. He is being very prominent in the Bori Convention in Indore.

02:02:44.920 --> 02:02:50.440
[Guest]: And if you noticed, in this Houston thing, there was a large number of bodies in that

02:02:50.440 --> 02:02:59.400
[Guest]: traditional attire. So Bori NRIs also obviously are being courted as part of this. I think

02:02:59.400 --> 02:03:08.360
[Guest]: there is a need to make that connect. And I think the most promising area, which I hope

02:03:08.360 --> 02:03:18.320
[Guest]: they will, is music. Because music is an area where there has been a lot of kind of commingling

02:03:18.320 --> 02:03:27.000
[Guest]: and a lot of emergence of a band of brothers spirit across Hindus and Muslims, not just

02:03:27.000 --> 02:03:33.560
[Guest]: within Hindus or within Muslims. It has been one of those things. We have in Tamil a song,

02:03:33.560 --> 02:03:40.800
[Guest]: Patum Nane, Bhavumum Nane. I am the song. I am the bhava. I am the feeling in the song.

02:03:40.800 --> 02:03:45.880
[Guest]: I am the person who has made you, the singer, sing. So this is Shiva, who is the lord of

02:03:45.880 --> 02:03:52.280
[Guest]: Madurai city. And we believe that still, if you are a good devoted person, you can still

02:03:52.280 --> 02:03:58.200
[Guest]: see, suddenly get to see Shiva in Madurai city. He is always there. So he is singing

02:03:58.200 --> 02:04:07.360
[Guest]: this song. And the person who wrote this, this is a 1970s, 60s, 70s song, is a guy called

02:04:07.360 --> 02:04:18.520
[Guest]: Kamu Sharif, a Muslim lyricist and poet. So my point is, if you can go to the Sufi Convention,

02:04:18.520 --> 02:04:25.600
[Guest]: then you should now also push along these things. Because otherwise, the narrative,

02:04:25.600 --> 02:04:30.920
[Guest]: including what is bothering me, is international. It is no longer just an Indian problem. It's

02:04:30.920 --> 02:04:38.640
[Guest]: got international dimensions in terms of this othering, that we need to, and I am hopeful.

02:04:38.640 --> 02:04:46.560
[Guest]: I somehow feel that the two countries where we might also get constructive response from

02:04:46.560 --> 02:04:52.480
[Guest]: Muslim intellectuals will be India and Indonesia, where they will come up with new pathbreaking

02:04:52.480 --> 02:05:02.200
[Guest]: ways to reach out to create band of brothers, affinities. I am very intrigued by this Pasmandha

02:05:02.200 --> 02:05:04.160
[Guest]: Muslim movement. You know about it?

02:05:04.160 --> 02:05:05.160
[Guest]: No.

02:05:05.160 --> 02:05:12.160
[Guest]: This is a movement in UP and Bihar of OBC Muslims. So they want to, so in a sense, they

02:05:12.160 --> 02:05:19.800
[Guest]: want, they're saying these Ashraf, you know, Arab, Persian descent, light complexion, Muslim

02:05:19.800 --> 02:05:27.080
[Guest]: aristocracy, they have not helped us. They've just, you know, taken care of their sinecures.

02:05:27.080 --> 02:05:34.440
[Guest]: So let us do our own movement, look for reservations, which is what everybody in India looks for

02:05:34.440 --> 02:05:41.520
[Guest]: and a few other goodies. But in the process, what are they doing? They are admitting that

02:05:41.520 --> 02:05:50.560
[Guest]: they are converts of OBC castes, which is what in fact, the Hindutva people want them

02:05:50.560 --> 02:05:58.080
[Guest]: to admit. So it is happening maybe for a totally different reason. But it's, so I am this girl

02:05:58.080 --> 02:06:05.240
[Guest]: Salma who writes, she's a Tamil feminist writer. She's a Muslim feminist writer. Very interesting.

02:06:05.240 --> 02:06:13.800
[Guest]: So there are things like that that are happening, which give me a sense of optimism. But yes,

02:06:13.800 --> 02:06:23.200
[Guest]: we could, the descent from high watermark 1930 to 1940 was just 10 years. It doesn't

02:06:23.200 --> 02:06:31.680
[Guest]: take very long. If you, if you make a few wrong choices, you could, hopefully again,

02:06:31.680 --> 02:06:36.920
[Guest]: that's the constitution. It is it's the inherent good sense of the Indian people which will

02:06:36.920 --> 02:06:37.920
[Amit Varma]: prevail.

02:06:37.920 --> 02:06:42.960
[Amit Varma]: In fact, one of the great lessons of the 20th century was that one must be able to tell

02:06:42.960 --> 02:06:47.560
[Amit Varma]: the difference between an ideology in its utopian form, as you've pointed out, and what

02:06:47.560 --> 02:06:52.760
[Amit Varma]: actually happens. And we've seen that with the Soviet Union, China, Cambodia, or whatever,

02:06:52.760 --> 02:06:57.440
[Amit Varma]: where you still have people who defend communism and say that in any theory, but practice where

02:06:57.440 --> 02:07:02.760
[Amit Varma]: they implemented it wrong. So my question to you then is, let's look at this school

02:07:02.760 --> 02:07:07.320
[Amit Varma]: of conservatism, the Bankimchandra school of conservatism with the same scepticism,

02:07:07.320 --> 02:07:12.640
[Amit Varma]: and leave aside what are in theory, the sensible aspects of it and look at what's happening

02:07:12.640 --> 02:07:16.920
[Amit Varma]: in practice, because what I see in practice is when Modi is a master of optics, what I

02:07:16.920 --> 02:07:22.520
[Amit Varma]: see in practice is that in terms of economics, his government is as statist as any government

02:07:22.520 --> 02:07:26.040
[Amit Varma]: in our history. In fact, many of the things he's done like demonetization and the botched

02:07:26.040 --> 02:07:30.480
[Amit Varma]: implementation of GST feels like it's right out of Indira Gandhi's book, I always say

02:07:30.480 --> 02:07:31.480
[Guest]: he's her successor.

02:07:31.480 --> 02:07:38.240
[Guest]: This is where I keep making the argument, we need to appeal to the non statist free

02:07:38.240 --> 02:07:44.720
[Guest]: market elements within the BJP. Because there are Luddite elements also, they don't want

02:07:44.720 --> 02:07:50.480
[Guest]: modern technology, but they don't want GM crops. There's there's a whole lot of elements

02:07:50.480 --> 02:07:59.400
[Guest]: within this broad umbrella of Hindu nationalism, which we need to neutralize and appeal to

02:07:59.400 --> 02:08:04.080
[Guest]: those elements which are, that's why I said if you read that again, there is something

02:08:04.080 --> 02:08:13.760
[Guest]: about technical thing, chic contemporary edge. Now, this meeting with Facebook, this interested

02:08:13.760 --> 02:08:17.680
[Guest]: in Silicon Valley, these are the things that we need to push.

02:08:17.680 --> 02:08:26.200
[Guest]: It's very tough, it's very tough to push it because the other side which wants GM crops

02:08:26.200 --> 02:08:32.640
[Guest]: to be banned, which wants no privatization, they have their, you know, they're playing

02:08:32.640 --> 02:08:42.640
[Guest]: the same game of using their thing. And, but it's a tough one. In general, it's been disappointing

02:08:42.640 --> 02:08:47.920
[Guest]: that this dispensation has not been as market friendly, I think, as many of us expected

02:08:47.920 --> 02:08:48.920
[Amit Varma]: it to be.

02:08:48.920 --> 02:08:52.200
[Amit Varma]: And I didn't really even finish my question, because the second part of the first part,

02:08:52.200 --> 02:08:55.880
[Amit Varma]: of course, is an economics have been completely statist, not even just as market friendly

02:08:55.880 --> 02:09:00.800
[Amit Varma]: as you and I would have liked, but literally Indira Gandhi level statist. But also in terms

02:09:00.800 --> 02:09:06.400
[Amit Varma]: of society, our society is being polarized very deeply. And I don't think that's an exaggeration

02:09:06.400 --> 02:09:08.720
[Amit Varma]: by what is really going on.

02:09:08.720 --> 02:09:15.240
[Guest]: I think it's an exaggeration. In my travels, I don't see, I think it's a very Bombay Delhi

02:09:15.240 --> 02:09:25.240
[Guest]: view. When I travel around the country, I don't see any great change from the past.

02:09:25.240 --> 02:09:34.320
[Guest]: And I really, you know, wonder if in fact, there is extraordinary new levels of violence

02:09:34.320 --> 02:09:43.280
[Guest]: or new levels of tension, because it seems to me pretty much the same as it was before.

02:09:43.280 --> 02:09:51.120
[Guest]: And it's India's never been an easy country to govern. And it's never been a nonviolent

02:09:51.120 --> 02:09:59.040
[Guest]: country despite Mahatma Gandhi's best efforts. So it's there, but it's I don't the narrative

02:09:59.040 --> 02:10:04.880
[Guest]: that somehow it has gone up dramatically in the last five, six years, I, I'm very sceptical

02:10:04.880 --> 02:10:11.080
[Guest]: of that narrative. For instance, take this some guy has gone to a magistrate and gotten

02:10:11.080 --> 02:10:16.560
[Guest]: some sedition case against some writers in some obscure court in Bihar. Now, this kind

02:10:16.560 --> 02:10:20.560
[Guest]: of thing has been happening in India for the last 80 years. It's not new.

02:10:20.560 --> 02:10:25.760
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I have in fact written about the sedition law in columns long before this government

02:10:25.760 --> 02:10:29.080
[Amit Varma]: came to power. But I think we'll agree to disagree. Because I think if you just look

02:10:29.080 --> 02:10:33.720
[Amit Varma]: at the number of the lynching numbers, for example, and the way that the discourse has

02:10:33.720 --> 02:10:37.920
[Amit Varma]: been so polarized and has become so shrill, I think, but we can agree to disagree.

02:10:37.920 --> 02:10:43.120
[Guest]: I don't know, I think maybe I have a longer memory or whatever. But have you heard of

02:10:43.120 --> 02:10:51.480
[Guest]: Kela Venmani? No. Kela Venmani in 1968, 40 odd Dalit agricultural workers were burnt

02:10:51.480 --> 02:11:01.080
[Guest]: alive in a, in a hut in Thanjavur district. Now, these kinds of things have been there

02:11:01.080 --> 02:11:07.160
[Guest]: and no one was punished, by the way. Commission of inquiry came up with some total anodyne

02:11:07.160 --> 02:11:13.520
[Guest]: report. And this is under a DMK government, not even a Congress government. I'm not, not,

02:11:13.520 --> 02:11:21.600
[Guest]: this is the, the, the, the, I remember so many of these things and I say Maliana, Meerut,

02:11:21.600 --> 02:11:26.640
[Guest]: Moradabad. In fact, this fellow who has now become governor of Kerala, what's his name?

02:11:26.640 --> 02:11:30.440
[Guest]: Arif Mohammad Khan. He makes an interesting statement. I was watching him on YouTube the

02:11:30.440 --> 02:11:36.640
[Guest]: other day. There have been no riots for some time. That's his perspective, you know, but

02:11:36.640 --> 02:11:42.640
[Guest]: which is actually interesting. You want to measure by riots. It's kind of horrifying

02:11:42.640 --> 02:11:46.680
[Guest]: idea because you know, the moment you say these things, you'll have one. It's kind of

02:11:46.680 --> 02:11:52.440
[Amit Varma]: scary, but. We'll leave this particular issue there. Let the listener decide. I've taken

02:11:52.440 --> 02:11:57.960
[Amit Varma]: a lot of your time. So I'll end with sort of a couple of more questions. One question

02:11:57.960 --> 02:12:05.600
[Amit Varma]: is that once you get into politics, your imperatives, your incentives drive you in a particular direction.

02:12:05.600 --> 02:12:10.200
[Amit Varma]: And typically what happens is you're driven by the will to power. For example, Amit Shah

02:12:10.200 --> 02:12:15.160
[Amit Varma]: is of course a master political strategist and the way he's done his mergers and acquisitions

02:12:15.160 --> 02:12:19.680
[Amit Varma]: got politicians from all parties, regardless of their founding ideology, the way he's put

02:12:19.680 --> 02:12:25.120
[Amit Varma]: together caste coalitions, you know, going after non-Yadav OBCs and non-Jatav Dalits

02:12:25.120 --> 02:12:29.160
[Amit Varma]: and so on and you'll be very masterful, but driven by the will to power and not by any

02:12:29.160 --> 02:12:36.680
[Amit Varma]: ideology per se. So then the question is that given that political imperatives leave you

02:12:36.680 --> 02:12:42.200
[Amit Varma]: with only one aim, which is what is the best way to come to power and nothing else matters,

02:12:42.200 --> 02:12:47.160
[Amit Varma]: not issues of virtue, or what is the right thing to do, or what is good for society,

02:12:47.160 --> 02:12:53.160
[Amit Varma]: but simply how do I win the next election? Is that something that you see as a problem?

02:12:53.160 --> 02:13:01.120
[Guest]: And isn't that a more core? It is. It would be a complete violation of the principles

02:13:01.120 --> 02:13:06.880
[Guest]: of Rajadharma. Thiruvalluvar certainly would not have approved of it. But all that is theory,

02:13:06.880 --> 02:13:15.200
[Guest]: right? No, why? I mean, I mean, ruling righteously is not theory. Who has ruled righteously?

02:13:15.200 --> 02:13:19.080
[Guest]: I mean, I don't like the word rule because they should serve, but who has ruled righteously?

02:13:19.080 --> 02:13:25.680
[Guest]: Not perfectly. Look, you go back to the American Constitution. They are saying more perfect

02:13:25.680 --> 02:13:33.080
[Guest]: union. They're not saying the perfect union. We are not saying that we can get it all correct.

02:13:33.080 --> 02:13:39.040
[Guest]: But the intention and the attempt has to be in the direction of righteousness and not

02:13:39.040 --> 02:13:44.960
[Guest]: in the direction of pure pursuit of power. And that is that is a danger. It's a danger

02:13:44.960 --> 02:13:55.680
[Guest]: that all kings, all quasi kings, would be kings, wannabe kings are tempted by. And in

02:13:55.680 --> 02:14:04.680
[Guest]: that process, will they adopt means that are not just moderately bad, but extremely bad?

02:14:04.680 --> 02:14:12.520
[Guest]: That's the question you're asking, right? And we've seen this again and again and again

02:14:12.520 --> 02:14:18.280
[Guest]: in democratic politics when somebody says, yeah, that might be a good idea, but it's

02:14:18.280 --> 02:14:24.920
[Guest]: not a vote winner. Oh, that's a vote loser. Forget it. You know, this idea that we will

02:14:24.920 --> 02:14:33.120
[Guest]: only pursue vote winners and discard vote losers is in and of itself not bad. But when

02:14:33.120 --> 02:14:42.120
[Guest]: you then say, I don't mind pursuing vote winners, but I'll do it through bribery, chauvinism,

02:14:42.120 --> 02:14:49.680
[Guest]: corruption, violence, that's when it becomes it becomes a problem. I don't think we've

02:14:49.680 --> 02:14:55.440
[Guest]: gotten there. The country is not there. Could it get there? I doubt it.

02:14:55.440 --> 02:15:01.640
[Amit Varma]: No, in the sense that we had something like demonetization, which was horrible economics,

02:15:01.640 --> 02:15:06.240
[Amit Varma]: but good politics and carried out for political reasons, because the calculation was that

02:15:06.240 --> 02:15:11.160
[Amit Varma]: one your opposition parties funds get stunted and to the sense of schadenfreude that the

02:15:11.160 --> 02:15:15.680
[Amit Varma]: poor feel about the rich suffering more than them will help them win the next UP election.

02:15:15.680 --> 02:15:16.680
[Guest]: And it was a landslide.

02:15:16.680 --> 02:15:24.760
[Guest]: You know, again, I mean, we, after the fact, it looks, if they had lost, we'd have said

02:15:24.760 --> 02:15:31.200
[Guest]: demonetization caused them the loss. My point is, after these electoral analysis, but why

02:15:31.200 --> 02:15:34.440
[Guest]: somebody wins or loses after the fact.

02:15:34.440 --> 02:15:41.080
[Amit Varma]: No, I agree with you. My point of bringing this up was to say that the impetus behind

02:15:41.080 --> 02:15:46.480
[Amit Varma]: a particular that particular economic policy and my contention is, for most economic policies

02:15:46.480 --> 02:15:51.280
[Guest]: that get carried out by the government is a political impetus, not an economic impetus.

02:15:51.280 --> 02:15:56.200
[Guest]: That is correct. And that's that is the nature of democracy. I don't think you can stand

02:15:56.200 --> 02:16:01.840
[Guest]: up in Britain and say NHS is inefficient. You will lose. It doesn't matter whether you're

02:16:01.840 --> 02:16:09.900
[Guest]: conservative or Labour or whatever. So yes, ultimately, in a democracy, politics predominates

02:16:09.900 --> 02:16:21.360
[Guest]: and not economics. And that has been one of the sadder things about the 1991 reforms,

02:16:21.360 --> 02:16:29.280
[Guest]: is that it wasn't sold to the people as something that's good to this day. I don't think it's

02:16:29.280 --> 02:16:33.240
[Guest]: economic reform or movement towards markets has been sold by anyone.

02:16:33.240 --> 02:16:37.480
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it's remarkable that actually the best thing in terms of policy that happened

02:16:37.480 --> 02:16:42.800
[Amit Varma]: to this country, which got 300 million people out of poverty, is something that Rahul Gandhi

02:16:42.800 --> 02:16:48.240
[Amit Varma]: actually disowns, and wants to walk back to earlier socialist times, which kept millions

02:16:48.240 --> 02:16:53.880
[Guest]: in poor, which is, you know, the state of the opposition is so dismal.

02:16:53.880 --> 02:17:01.040
[Guest]: Because I think the politics of patronage may be very important for their votes. Right.

02:17:01.040 --> 02:17:05.680
[Guest]: In other words, you know, exactly the point I was making, I made this point many years

02:17:05.680 --> 02:17:11.080
[Guest]: ago, to one of my friends of the Congress. I'm talking about 20-30 years ago, not now.

02:17:11.080 --> 02:17:17.680
[Guest]: I said, yeah, as far as I can make out, the less educated a person is, the less wealthy

02:17:17.680 --> 02:17:25.280
[Guest]: a person is, other things being equal, caste, gender, etc. The more likely that person is

02:17:25.280 --> 02:17:33.280
[Guest]: to work for Congress party. Therefore, I said, you guys have a vested interest in keeping

02:17:33.280 --> 02:17:40.640
[Guest]: people less educated and less wealthy. I mean, stupid reverse causality, I admit, it's not

02:17:40.640 --> 02:17:48.160
[Guest]: a good argument. But I was making it for effect to say, these are very complicated things.

02:17:48.160 --> 02:17:58.480
[Guest]: They don't, for instance, would you want Hispanic Americans to get integrated? If you are a

02:17:58.480 --> 02:18:05.640
[Guest]: Democratic Party leader in America, probably not, you want to highlight their separateness,

02:18:05.640 --> 02:18:09.440
[Guest]: because then they'll vote for you. Otherwise, they might vote Republican. So these are some

02:18:09.440 --> 02:18:16.280
[Guest]: very complicated things. And it's a curse of democracy, that we have to deal with these

02:18:16.280 --> 02:18:24.120
[Guest]: things. I think economic reform, we have to keep fighting for it on only two, three basis.

02:18:24.120 --> 02:18:33.040
[Guest]: One, it is morally the right thing to do, Raja Dharma, not to interfere in economic

02:18:33.040 --> 02:18:41.560
[Guest]: activities of your citizens. Two, consequentially, all these Asian countries who adopted it have

02:18:41.560 --> 02:18:48.660
[Guest]: done better than us. Therefore, you will do better. And three, if a constituency keeps

02:18:48.660 --> 02:18:54.080
[Guest]: getting built for it, which is still very small, presumably, and not a constituency

02:18:54.080 --> 02:19:01.120
[Guest]: for freebies, I think you might, but the third one is very tough. It's very tough. Politics

02:19:01.120 --> 02:19:09.560
[Guest]: always trumps economics. And also they look at the facts. Fact is Nassim Rao lost. Fact

02:19:09.560 --> 02:19:15.400
[Guest]: is Vajpayee lost. You know, hey, wait a minute, probably our two best Prime Ministers. Wait

02:19:15.400 --> 02:19:19.720
[Guest]: a minute, you know, economic reform, Vajpayee did the maximum amount of privatizations,

02:19:19.720 --> 02:19:27.720
[Guest]: even added disinvestment ministry. He lost. So the conclusion you come to, it's a very

02:19:27.720 --> 02:19:35.560
[Guest]: strange conclusion, but you come to it that, hey, you know, the voters are supreme. And

02:19:35.560 --> 02:19:44.280
[Guest]: how does one deal with that? Democracy is not an unmixed blessing. It has its problems,

02:19:44.280 --> 02:19:49.160
[Guest]: as Churchill says, it's better than other systems, but it's not necessarily a very good

02:19:49.160 --> 02:19:50.160
[Amit Varma]: system.

02:19:50.160 --> 02:19:54.840
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely. Now, I'll let you go shortly. I'll release you from the fetters of this

02:19:54.840 --> 02:20:00.000
[Amit Varma]: drab podcast recording studio. But before I ask my final question, I just want a word

02:20:00.000 --> 02:20:04.520
[Amit Varma]: for my listeners. I had four pages of notes for this episode, and I'm through just two

02:20:04.520 --> 02:20:11.240
[Amit Varma]: of them. Among the things we could not discuss is the development of Islam in India, how

02:20:11.240 --> 02:20:17.360
[Amit Varma]: much of it was around conservative lines, how much was not. Jerry's assertion that Jinnah

02:20:17.360 --> 02:20:22.160
[Amit Varma]: started off as a conservative and ended as a radical. Then there are a couple of really

02:20:22.160 --> 02:20:28.680
[Amit Varma]: good chapters on culture, on society, on aesthetics and education. So the book is far richer than

02:20:28.680 --> 02:20:32.160
[Amit Varma]: this, even this episode might have given you a sense of so please to go out and buy the

02:20:32.160 --> 02:20:36.800
[Amit Varma]: book. But now for my last question, which is a question I ask all my guests about whatever

02:20:36.800 --> 02:20:43.280
[Guest]: the subject is. Can I come in for one minute? Particularly the culture section, I think

02:20:43.280 --> 02:20:51.280
[Guest]: is something that I spent a fair amount of time and effort on. Because the problem in

02:20:51.280 --> 02:20:58.840
[Guest]: today's academia, both in North America and in England and in the continent and in India,

02:20:58.840 --> 02:21:05.580
[Guest]: is that it's dominated by Marxist postmodernists and Freudians, who have kind of dismissed

02:21:05.580 --> 02:21:12.080
[Guest]: the idea of an Indian culture as upper caste, hegemonic, patriarchal, this, that and the

02:21:12.080 --> 02:21:18.560
[Guest]: other using their vocabulary that postmodernists like, which I don't understand, and I choose

02:21:18.560 --> 02:21:28.480
[Guest]: not to understand. And I've taken a very comprehensive and a very head on attack on that, in defending

02:21:28.480 --> 02:21:34.520
[Guest]: the idea of an Indian culture. So I do hope readers will get to that and spend time on

02:21:34.520 --> 02:21:42.760
[Amit Varma]: that. Now, come on your question. Yeah, my final question is, speaking as a conservative,

02:21:42.760 --> 02:21:50.600
[Amit Varma]: what gives you hope? And what gives you despair about the next 20 years in India?

02:21:50.600 --> 02:22:02.000
[Guest]: What gives me hope? I think, basically, the residual Marxism residual socialism, as an

02:22:02.000 --> 02:22:10.360
[Guest]: intellectually coherent and respectable doctrine will go away. There is still left. I think

02:22:10.360 --> 02:22:14.600
[Guest]: it will go away. That gives me hope. Because as long as it exists, it's always a danger

02:22:14.600 --> 02:22:21.000
[Guest]: and a bad thing. I think in the economics area, either because of a crisis or whatever

02:22:21.000 --> 02:22:29.280
[Guest]: reason, the philosophy of supporting markets and being market friendly, will willy nilly

02:22:29.280 --> 02:22:36.440
[Guest]: reassert itself. I think Indian culture is thriving. On that score, I'm quite positive.

02:22:36.440 --> 02:22:43.440
[Guest]: I think Indian social change is going along fairly okay lines. There are issues like Sabarimala

02:22:43.440 --> 02:22:50.800
[Guest]: and so on, which kind of distract us. But in general, it is it is moving along the directions.

02:22:50.800 --> 02:23:02.400
[Guest]: Now what am I worried about? I think one worry is that we continue to not recognize, intellectually

02:23:02.400 --> 02:23:09.320
[Guest]: at least, in sufficient numbers, the continuity in our history, particularly the importance

02:23:09.320 --> 02:23:16.080
[Guest]: of the British Raj as an important, constructive, positive intervention in Indian history. If

02:23:16.080 --> 02:23:22.480
[Guest]: we don't, then we run the risk of doing stupid things. And that is a big risk that worries

02:23:22.480 --> 02:23:27.600
[Guest]: me again. And I see it in our neighboring states. I see it in Myanmar. I see it in Sri

02:23:27.600 --> 02:23:34.240
[Guest]: Lanka. I see it in Pakistan. I see it in all of the former colonies of the British in Africa.

02:23:34.240 --> 02:23:38.680
[Guest]: And Naipaul talks about it when he talks about mimic men. You know, what does he say? That's

02:23:38.680 --> 02:23:44.800
[Guest]: what he's talking about. The jettisoning of that is and it could happen. It could happen

02:23:44.800 --> 02:23:49.880
[Guest]: because there is so little understanding and so little defense of it. In fact, the most

02:23:49.880 --> 02:23:56.000
[Guest]: popular books recently in Indian history have been attacking Robert Clive and attacking

02:23:56.000 --> 02:24:01.320
[Guest]: East India Company without, you know, and very popular, immensely popular among Indians,

02:24:01.320 --> 02:24:07.400
[Guest]: middle classes and upwardly middle class. That worries me. That's a big worry I have.

02:24:07.400 --> 02:24:18.200
[Guest]: Then I do have a concern that which you expressed that, you know, essentially we have moved

02:24:18.200 --> 02:24:27.480
[Guest]: far ahead politically without moving sufficiently economically or socially. The same issues

02:24:27.480 --> 02:24:35.680
[Guest]: that Rana Dey raised 120 years ago. Please let us not go for, you know, quick political

02:24:35.680 --> 02:24:42.280
[Guest]: freedom without concomitant economic and social change. That is still the curse that we are

02:24:42.280 --> 02:24:48.640
[Guest]: living with. And that means you never know. We could have some very strange and bizarre

02:24:48.640 --> 02:24:57.840
[Guest]: political behavior. And we should always be very careful. The First Republic of India

02:24:57.840 --> 02:25:09.520
[Guest]: is 69 years old, yes. And, you know, it is very important that we collectively say, hey,

02:25:09.520 --> 02:25:17.920
[Guest]: we want to be around in the same fashion more or less 69 years from now. And 1776 to 1860

02:25:17.920 --> 02:25:25.200
[Guest]: was how many years? 84 years. A major crisis happened in the history of the other great

02:25:25.200 --> 02:25:31.920
[Guest]: constitutional republic that we are aware of. So those these are dangerous times in

02:25:31.920 --> 02:25:38.440
[Guest]: the history of any republic. We are no longer young. We're a middling, middle aged republic.

02:25:38.440 --> 02:25:42.920
[Guest]: And middle age is when, you know, as you know, cholesterol and diabetes and all these things

02:25:42.920 --> 02:25:49.280
[Guest]: hit people. And that could be true for a society, too. So that gives me sleepless nights.

